00:05:05.030 --> 00:05:07.100
One reason for
such great interest

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:09.650
in a conference about
sports and gender

00:05:09.650 --> 00:05:13.860
is that the topic is both
very timely and timeless.

00:05:13.860 --> 00:05:16.730
Its current relevance
is all around us.

00:05:16.730 --> 00:05:20.090
Athletic teams at Harvard and
at many other universities

00:05:20.090 --> 00:05:24.020
this year have had to confront
troubling demonstrations

00:05:24.020 --> 00:05:27.260
of demeaning attitudes
towards female athletes.

00:05:27.260 --> 00:05:30.110
Just last week, the
US women's hockey team

00:05:30.110 --> 00:05:34.160
made the news when they struck
an unprecedented deal with USA

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:36.440
hockey for higher wages.

00:05:39.230 --> 00:05:41.450
All it took was the
threat of a boycott,

00:05:41.450 --> 00:05:44.930
15 months of tense
negotiations, and an open letter

00:05:44.930 --> 00:05:47.970
from 16 US senators.

00:05:47.970 --> 00:05:51.120
The questions raised by
the intersection of gender

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:54.210
and sports are certainly
newsworthy today,

00:05:54.210 --> 00:05:56.220
but those questions
have been present

00:05:56.220 --> 00:05:59.100
around the world
for much of history.

00:05:59.100 --> 00:06:02.340
Early artwork from ancient
Egypt to medieval Europe

00:06:02.340 --> 00:06:05.070
featured male and
female human figures

00:06:05.070 --> 00:06:07.680
swinging at balls with sticks.

00:06:07.680 --> 00:06:09.870
But despite their
widespread appearance

00:06:09.870 --> 00:06:13.800
across many times and places,
neither sports nor gender

00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:15.360
are unchanging.

00:06:15.360 --> 00:06:18.550
Both are shaped by social,
political, economic,

00:06:18.550 --> 00:06:20.250
and cultural context.

00:06:20.250 --> 00:06:22.350
Let me give you an example.

00:06:22.350 --> 00:06:25.880
In the early decades of
the 19th century, sports

00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:29.610
we're actually regarded
poorly in Western society.

00:06:29.610 --> 00:06:34.020
Games were all very well for
children, but for adults sports

00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:35.880
were morally suspect.

00:06:35.880 --> 00:06:38.940
Men who aspired
social respectability

00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:41.970
rejected popular sports
like prizefighting

00:06:41.970 --> 00:06:47.190
as vulgar and overly physical
pastimes of the lower classes.

00:06:47.190 --> 00:06:48.810
But by the
mid-nineteenth century,

00:06:48.810 --> 00:06:52.320
things began to change
with new movement called

00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:54.420
muscular Christianity.

00:06:54.420 --> 00:06:57.030
Beginning in England and
spreading to the Northeastern

00:06:57.030 --> 00:07:00.120
United States,
muscular Christianity

00:07:00.120 --> 00:07:03.900
equated physical fitness
with moral health,

00:07:03.900 --> 00:07:06.870
and linked both to masculinity.

00:07:06.870 --> 00:07:09.120
In order for members
of the upper class,

00:07:09.120 --> 00:07:11.670
both men and women,
to claim sports

00:07:11.670 --> 00:07:14.640
as elite and respectable,
however, sports

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:18.780
had to be repackaged from
a rough and tumble pastime

00:07:18.780 --> 00:07:21.970
into an activity
befitting gentlemen.

00:07:21.970 --> 00:07:24.510
And it wasn't an
easy shift to make.

00:07:24.510 --> 00:07:27.630
As late as 1859,
Harper's Magazine

00:07:27.630 --> 00:07:31.470
insisted that grown adults
who indulged in sports

00:07:31.470 --> 00:07:35.640
must be either, and I
quote, "milksops or bad me."

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:38.940
How then, did proponent's
of athleticism

00:07:38.940 --> 00:07:43.170
finally legitimize men's
participation in sports?

00:07:43.170 --> 00:07:46.230
Promoters of sporting
events began inviting women

00:07:46.230 --> 00:07:49.890
to sports games in an effort
to infuse those events

00:07:49.890 --> 00:07:53.580
with the values of Victorian
womanhood such as refinement,

00:07:53.580 --> 00:07:55.950
delicacy, and propriety.

00:07:55.950 --> 00:07:59.340
Team owners provided special
tents and refreshments

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:03.360
for women spectators, and
women assumed specific roles

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:08.310
such as presenting bouquets or
game balls to winning teams.

00:08:08.310 --> 00:08:11.490
For sports to become
more respectable for men,

00:08:11.490 --> 00:08:15.540
both men and women
took on new roles.

00:08:15.540 --> 00:08:19.890
Of course, in 1860, women's
roles were decidedly limited.

00:08:19.890 --> 00:08:21.660
They could attend games.

00:08:21.660 --> 00:08:24.330
They could bestow
flowers on winners.

00:08:24.330 --> 00:08:26.940
They could even play
a number of sports,

00:08:26.940 --> 00:08:30.300
so long as they
didn't keep score.

00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:34.350
As for competing, only men were
supposed to do that for fear

00:08:34.350 --> 00:08:38.010
that competition might
make women too coarse.

00:08:38.010 --> 00:08:42.090
It should be clear that
sports provide a powerful lens

00:08:42.090 --> 00:08:45.280
for understanding
much larger questions

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:47.640
of an historical
time, and sports

00:08:47.640 --> 00:08:52.650
continue to offer that
similar critical lens today.

00:08:52.650 --> 00:08:55.410
Now as then, sport
and gender are

00:08:55.410 --> 00:08:57.760
inseparable from each other.

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:02.310
Now as then, gender disparity
is a major characteristic

00:09:02.310 --> 00:09:03.780
of sports.

00:09:03.780 --> 00:09:07.620
Today, women compete,
but not on equal footing.

00:09:07.620 --> 00:09:11.760
Even in tennis, the sport
lauded for coming closest to pay

00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:14.730
equity, discrepancies remain.

00:09:14.730 --> 00:09:19.980
In 2015, Roger Federer won the
men's Western and Southern open

00:09:19.980 --> 00:09:23.250
and received more than $700,000.

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:26.610
Just hours later, Serena
Williams, arguably

00:09:26.610 --> 00:09:30.690
the world's most outstanding
athlete, won the women's title

00:09:30.690 --> 00:09:35.060
and she collected a prize
of less than $500,000.

00:09:35.060 --> 00:09:38.510
If inequities between men
and women have persisted,

00:09:38.510 --> 00:09:42.080
in other ways the relationship
between sport and gender

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:44.280
has changed over time.

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:47.030
We now face questions
about steroid use

00:09:47.030 --> 00:09:50.090
and athletic performance,
neurological damage

00:09:50.090 --> 00:09:54.800
while competing, and the rights
of transgender participants.

00:09:54.800 --> 00:09:59.180
These questions and more require
an interdisciplinary approach

00:09:59.180 --> 00:10:03.260
capable of considering the many
complexities of gender, sports,

00:10:03.260 --> 00:10:04.640
and society.

00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:07.740
That is what brings
us all here today.

00:10:07.740 --> 00:10:09.890
I just want to say
before we move on

00:10:09.890 --> 00:10:13.190
that we want to treat
you to a reception

00:10:13.190 --> 00:10:15.920
at the end of the
day at Fei House

00:10:15.920 --> 00:10:18.170
to celebrate our
panelists and organizers.

00:10:18.170 --> 00:10:21.170
So I look forward to
talking with you then.

00:10:21.170 --> 00:10:23.390
It is now my pleasure
to turn things over

00:10:23.390 --> 00:10:26.570
to Susan Ware, who will
moderate the first panel.

00:10:26.570 --> 00:10:29.240
Susan is an acclaimed
historian and the biographer

00:10:29.240 --> 00:10:32.570
of such notable figures as
Billie Jean King and Amelia

00:10:32.570 --> 00:10:35.390
Earhart, as well as the
editor of the latest

00:10:35.390 --> 00:10:37.550
volume of Notable
American Women,

00:10:37.550 --> 00:10:39.320
a biographical dictionary.

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:42.410
Susan currently serves as
general editor of the American

00:10:42.410 --> 00:10:45.830
National Biography and she
is also the honorary Women's

00:10:45.830 --> 00:10:48.710
Suffrage Centennial Historian
at the Schlesinger Library,

00:10:48.710 --> 00:10:49.850
here at Radcliffe.

00:10:49.850 --> 00:10:52.080
Please join me in
welcoming Susan Ware.

00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:54.455
[APPLAUSE]

00:10:56.830 --> 00:10:58.320
- Good morning.

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:03.840
Thanks so much for coming and
very glad to have you here.

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:08.370
This session is organized around
a seemingly straightforward

00:11:08.370 --> 00:11:11.280
question, who gets to play?

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:13.110
Yet like many of
the other issues

00:11:13.110 --> 00:11:16.950
we'll be discussing today,
the answer is far from simple,

00:11:16.950 --> 00:11:19.140
and certainly not static.

00:11:19.140 --> 00:11:22.380
Our main focus is on
what role gender plays

00:11:22.380 --> 00:11:24.720
in access to
sports, but we can't

00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:27.090
address that in isolation.

00:11:27.090 --> 00:11:29.130
So we'll also be
exploring questions

00:11:29.130 --> 00:11:33.930
of race, class, sexual
identity, and disability.

00:11:33.930 --> 00:11:37.380
We want to think carefully
about which sports

00:11:37.380 --> 00:11:40.410
we're talking about,
recreational sports,

00:11:40.410 --> 00:11:43.140
high school or
college athletics,

00:11:43.140 --> 00:11:47.070
international competitions,
or professional leagues.

00:11:47.070 --> 00:11:50.940
We want to explore how the
United States system conforms

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:56.250
to or differs from how sport
is organized around the world.

00:11:56.250 --> 00:12:00.660
We want to think about special
challenges to sports access.

00:12:00.660 --> 00:12:04.350
How can an athlete compete
in international competition

00:12:04.350 --> 00:12:08.280
if she's a stateless refugee
or cannot find the appropriate

00:12:08.280 --> 00:12:12.180
athletic gear to accommodate
her religious beliefs.

00:12:12.180 --> 00:12:15.570
We won't necessarily be able
to cover all of those topics,

00:12:15.570 --> 00:12:17.070
but we certainly
hope that we will

00:12:17.070 --> 00:12:19.950
start conversations
that will continue

00:12:19.950 --> 00:12:22.180
for the rest of the day.

00:12:22.180 --> 00:12:24.930
So in many ways,
in certain ways,

00:12:24.930 --> 00:12:27.480
this is the history panel.

00:12:27.480 --> 00:12:30.780
We're exploring how the
question, who gets to play,

00:12:30.780 --> 00:12:35.430
has changed over time, and
how this historical trajectory

00:12:35.430 --> 00:12:39.150
might influence who's
next in staking a claim.

00:12:39.150 --> 00:12:41.730
So it seems
especially appropriate

00:12:41.730 --> 00:12:46.650
that it's taking place in the
former Radcliffe gymnasium.

00:12:46.650 --> 00:12:49.800
One glorious summer
afternoon several years

00:12:49.800 --> 00:12:53.850
ago, I snuck into the
building in my running gear,

00:12:53.850 --> 00:12:59.790
and I ran 16 laps, a mile,
around the upper level track.

00:12:59.790 --> 00:13:05.160
And as I circled the gym,
I felt a literal connection

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:08.280
through the floorboards
to the generations

00:13:08.280 --> 00:13:12.960
of Radcliffe athletes who
had also run on that track.

00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:15.330
What must they
think, I wondered,

00:13:15.330 --> 00:13:19.680
of the opportunities available
to female athletes today.

00:13:19.680 --> 00:13:22.260
Opportunities that would
have been inconceivable

00:13:22.260 --> 00:13:26.070
in their time, indeed
inconceivable probably

00:13:26.070 --> 00:13:28.830
to certain members
of this audience.

00:13:28.830 --> 00:13:32.070
And yet-- and there's
always that catch--

00:13:32.070 --> 00:13:35.760
so much has happened, especially
in the last five decades,

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:39.810
and yet women athletes are
still nowhere near anything

00:13:39.810 --> 00:13:42.570
approaching gender
equity in athletics.

00:13:42.570 --> 00:13:46.680
So drawing up a balance sheet
between the undisputed progress

00:13:46.680 --> 00:13:51.630
in widening access versus the
ongoing structural and societal

00:13:51.630 --> 00:13:54.060
barriers to full
participation will

00:13:54.060 --> 00:13:56.780
be a recurring theme
of our panel, indeed,

00:13:56.780 --> 00:13:58.440
of the whole conference.

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:00.720
And it's especially
relevant to take stock

00:14:00.720 --> 00:14:05.160
as Title IX, the US law that
played such an important part

00:14:05.160 --> 00:14:07.890
in fostering the revolution
in women's sports,

00:14:07.890 --> 00:14:11.100
turns 45 this year,
which is a plug

00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:13.710
to visit the exhibit,
Documentary [INAUDIBLE] History

