00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:27.610
- So, it's my job in
this first 15 minutes

00:15:27.610 --> 00:15:31.090
to give you the
history of Title IX.

00:15:31.090 --> 00:15:33.190
From 30,000 feet,
give you a sense

00:15:33.190 --> 00:15:36.280
of what the current statistics
are and to answer the question,

00:15:36.280 --> 00:15:38.440
how close are we
to gender equity?

00:15:38.440 --> 00:15:42.820
And then I want to take a
view from ground zero look

00:15:42.820 --> 00:15:46.120
at Harvard's athletic program.

00:15:46.120 --> 00:15:48.190
Wherever I go to speak,
I always make sure

00:15:48.190 --> 00:15:52.120
that the home team gets
my attention, for sure.

00:15:52.120 --> 00:15:53.560
So let me see if this works.

00:15:53.560 --> 00:15:55.630
OK, so, this is quick and dirty.

00:15:55.630 --> 00:15:58.360
Research shows that the
faster the speaker speaks,

00:15:58.360 --> 00:16:00.400
the greater the
retention of the audience

00:16:00.400 --> 00:16:04.660
because you can't fall asleep.

00:16:04.660 --> 00:16:06.820
I learned that when I
went to my first job

00:16:06.820 --> 00:16:07.990
at the University of Texas.

00:16:07.990 --> 00:16:11.980
Everybody was kind of
scary in terms of Yankee

00:16:11.980 --> 00:16:13.350
speed of speech.

00:16:13.350 --> 00:16:16.330
Anyway, I've always
I've always referred

00:16:16.330 --> 00:16:20.830
to the civil rights laws in
the US as the perfect trifecta.

00:16:20.830 --> 00:16:24.310
They all use the same language,
whether it's the Civil Rights

00:16:24.310 --> 00:16:30.550
Act of 1964, or Title IX of
the 1972 education amendments,

00:16:30.550 --> 00:16:32.980
or the Rehabilitation
Act of 1973,

00:16:32.980 --> 00:16:35.620
followed by the
Disabilities Act of '93,

00:16:35.620 --> 00:16:37.600
it's all the same language.

00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:40.720
If you are receiving
federal funds,

00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:44.140
you cannot discriminate on
the basis of, and then fill

00:16:44.140 --> 00:16:45.880
in the blank.

00:16:45.880 --> 00:16:47.860
Very simple law.

00:16:47.860 --> 00:16:51.430
Nobody knew it applied to
intercollegiate athletics

00:16:51.430 --> 00:16:54.730
until the law firm,
the Washington D.C law

00:16:54.730 --> 00:17:00.730
firm the NCAA asked the
question, in early 1974,

00:17:00.730 --> 00:17:04.869
does it apply to
extracurricular activities?

00:17:04.869 --> 00:17:07.240
And the answer was
then yes, but you

00:17:07.240 --> 00:17:10.540
should know that Title IX
was never an athletics law.

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:13.569
It was fully intended
by Edith Green and Birch

00:17:13.569 --> 00:17:17.109
Bayh, who were the co-sponsors
of the original law,

00:17:17.109 --> 00:17:19.510
it was fully intended
to open the doors

00:17:19.510 --> 00:17:22.750
of professional graduate
education to women.

00:17:22.750 --> 00:17:25.510
It was an Equal Pay
Act issue at the time

00:17:25.510 --> 00:17:28.690
that they realized that women
couldn't get paid more if they

00:17:28.690 --> 00:17:30.412
didn't have advanced degrees.

00:17:30.412 --> 00:17:31.870
And there were
quotas on the number

00:17:31.870 --> 00:17:34.330
of women who were admitted
into medical school, who

00:17:34.330 --> 00:17:37.810
were admitted into law
school, who became engineers.

00:17:37.810 --> 00:17:39.880
If your father didn't
build a building,

00:17:39.880 --> 00:17:42.509
you didn't get
into those programs

00:17:42.509 --> 00:17:44.800
because they were afraid you
were going to have babies,

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:49.450
and your education would
be absolutely wasted.

00:17:49.450 --> 00:17:53.350
But anyway, so the
NCAA in 1974 says,

00:17:53.350 --> 00:17:57.250
does this law apply to
intercollegiate athletics

00:17:57.250 --> 00:17:59.080
and extracurricular activities?

00:17:59.080 --> 00:18:02.110
The answer is yes and
all hell breaks loose.

00:18:02.110 --> 00:18:04.750
Darrell Royal, who is then
the president of the American

00:18:04.750 --> 00:18:08.350
Football Coaches Association
was quoted across the country

00:18:08.350 --> 00:18:10.120
as "Title IX of
women's athletics

00:18:10.120 --> 00:18:13.460
would be the death of big
time football as we know it."

00:18:13.460 --> 00:18:15.900
Horrors, horrors to be.

00:18:15.900 --> 00:18:21.610
And one of the great things
about the entry of the football

00:18:21.610 --> 00:18:25.730
establishment was that it was
the invitation to the media

00:18:25.730 --> 00:18:28.150
to equally cover the issue.

00:18:28.150 --> 00:18:30.880
If Darrell said
this about what was

00:18:30.880 --> 00:18:32.740
going to happen
to football, what

00:18:32.740 --> 00:18:35.080
were the women going
to say in terms

00:18:35.080 --> 00:18:37.030
of the effect of Title IX?

00:18:37.030 --> 00:18:40.330
And the leaders of women's
athletics at the time

00:18:40.330 --> 00:18:42.750
were female physical educators.

00:18:42.750 --> 00:18:45.220
Well-educated,
they've researched

00:18:45.220 --> 00:18:49.480
the impact of sport
participation on girls,

00:18:49.480 --> 00:18:53.080
and they hit the media
with a salvo of research

00:18:53.080 --> 00:18:57.910
supported fact that to this
day has never been rivaled.

00:18:57.910 --> 00:18:58.810
They were quick.

00:18:58.810 --> 00:19:00.120
They didn't attack football.

00:19:00.120 --> 00:19:02.170
They were just
simply saying, guess

00:19:02.170 --> 00:19:06.340
what, girls who play sports
are less likely to experience

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:09.640
sexual harassment, are less
likely to get a heart attack.

00:19:09.640 --> 00:19:13.090
They just listed all the
physiological benefits

00:19:13.090 --> 00:19:14.680
of sport.

00:19:14.680 --> 00:19:17.260
Psychologically, they
have stronger self-images.

00:19:17.260 --> 00:19:20.440
They have higher levels
of competence, confidence,

00:19:20.440 --> 00:19:23.950
they are more likely to
succeed in life after sport.

00:19:23.950 --> 00:19:28.000
And the end question was
hey, sport does great things

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:29.560
for your son and your daughter.

00:19:29.560 --> 00:19:32.530
Do you want your son and
daughter to be treated equally?

00:19:32.530 --> 00:19:35.860
And the answer was
a resounding yes.

00:19:35.860 --> 00:19:40.300
So this benefits to
girls media message

00:19:40.300 --> 00:19:44.440
wielded by fact supporting--

00:19:44.440 --> 00:19:48.060
I know you haven't heard that
recently-- fact supporting

00:19:48.060 --> 00:19:53.380
women in the business
really made a dent in terms

00:19:53.380 --> 00:19:56.290
of public sentiment, and you
can see what the figures are

00:19:56.290 --> 00:19:59.260
in terms of the percentage
of the public that

00:19:59.260 --> 00:20:01.690
is in support of Title
IX, even if it means

00:20:01.690 --> 00:20:03.550
lost opportunities for men.

00:20:03.550 --> 00:20:05.860
And then the last point
to be made, historically,

00:20:05.860 --> 00:20:10.150
is it really was a
father led movement.

00:20:10.150 --> 00:20:13.250
Mom never had the
chance to play sports.

00:20:13.250 --> 00:20:17.410
Dad all of a sudden had
a single point of contact

00:20:17.410 --> 00:20:19.600
with surrogate son.

00:20:19.600 --> 00:20:22.150
My daughter is playing sports.

00:20:22.150 --> 00:20:24.530
I can have a catch with
her in the backyard

00:20:24.530 --> 00:20:29.210
and the biggest advocates
of sport became fathers.

00:20:29.210 --> 00:20:32.510
And it was this
father-mother combo

00:20:32.510 --> 00:20:38.030
that really has been
responsible for the staying

00:20:38.030 --> 00:20:39.480
power of the law.

00:20:39.480 --> 00:20:42.830
Let me mention one more
piece of this puzzle.

00:20:42.830 --> 00:20:46.460
There was an accident
in history that

00:20:46.460 --> 00:20:49.100
ensured that Title IX could
never be tampered with,

00:20:49.100 --> 00:20:52.040
and that accident was when
the football coaches made

00:20:52.040 --> 00:20:53.900
their stink.

00:20:53.900 --> 00:20:57.920
Congress responded
by saying well,

00:20:57.920 --> 00:21:00.680
we'll make sure that the
regulations interpreting

00:21:00.680 --> 00:21:03.470
the law's application
to sport get

00:21:03.470 --> 00:21:08.990
issued before the law goes
into effect so everybody

00:21:08.990 --> 00:21:11.720
knows what the game's about.

00:21:11.720 --> 00:21:14.180
That never happens
to regulations.

00:21:14.180 --> 00:21:18.530
Usually a law
passes, it's debated

00:21:18.530 --> 00:21:20.900
in the courts for
10 years, and then

00:21:20.900 --> 00:21:23.600
regulations eventually evolve.

00:21:23.600 --> 00:21:26.940
In this case, tons
of regulations

00:21:26.940 --> 00:21:30.060
on the application of title
IX, specific to sports,

00:21:30.060 --> 00:21:33.630
were issued, and every
single court case

00:21:33.630 --> 00:21:36.660
has deferred to
those regulations.

00:21:36.660 --> 00:21:39.900
And you don't have any of the
disagreements in the court that

00:21:39.900 --> 00:21:43.200
typically follow the passage
of a new law like this.

00:21:43.200 --> 00:21:46.230
And I think that
accident of history

00:21:46.230 --> 00:21:52.890
is singularly responsible for
the stability of Title IX.

00:21:52.890 --> 00:21:55.350
All right, the view from
30,000 feet-- and I'm

00:21:55.350 --> 00:21:58.140
going to go through
this stuff very quickly.

00:21:58.140 --> 00:22:01.530
When you look at
high school sports,

00:22:01.530 --> 00:22:05.220
you're looking at
in 1971 and '72.

00:22:05.220 --> 00:22:08.010
Men having about 3.6
million opportunities

00:22:08.010 --> 00:22:12.120
to play compared to
294,000 for women.

00:22:12.120 --> 00:22:15.300
What is interesting is when you
look at it in '14-'15, the last

00:22:15.300 --> 00:22:16.770
available data.

00:22:16.770 --> 00:22:19.080
Women at the high
school level still

00:22:19.080 --> 00:22:21.690
have not achieved the
participation levels

00:22:21.690 --> 00:22:24.690
that men had in 1971.

00:22:24.690 --> 00:22:28.980
They are still 1.1 million
opportunities short

00:22:28.980 --> 00:22:31.170
from matching up
to their proportion

00:22:31.170 --> 00:22:32.340
in the general student body.

00:22:35.550 --> 00:22:39.510
One thing this data shows
us is that it has not

00:22:39.510 --> 00:22:41.340
been a zero sum game.

00:22:41.340 --> 00:22:43.500
The fears that the football
coaches and everybody

00:22:43.500 --> 00:22:45.960
else expressed
with Title IX where

00:22:45.960 --> 00:22:48.780
oh, if you give women the
chance to play then they're

00:22:48.780 --> 00:22:51.300
going to take opportunities
away from your son.

00:22:51.300 --> 00:22:54.690
And you can see from this
data that it never happened.

00:22:54.690 --> 00:22:57.030
Men's participation
and boys participation

00:22:57.030 --> 00:22:59.640
has continued to grow at the
high school and the college

00:22:59.640 --> 00:23:00.540
level.

00:23:00.540 --> 00:23:04.170
It has not been a zero sum
game, and interestingly,

00:23:04.170 --> 00:23:07.170
over the last decade,
men's participation

00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:10.160
has grown at a quicker rate.

00:23:10.160 --> 00:23:11.910
More opportunities
have been added for men

00:23:11.910 --> 00:23:15.210
than have been added for women,
despite the fact that women

00:23:15.210 --> 00:23:17.790
are still under-represented
in high school sports.

00:23:17.790 --> 00:23:20.730
The picture at the
college level is the same.

00:23:20.730 --> 00:23:22.960
It's almost identical.

00:23:22.960 --> 00:23:28.920
So you're looking at numbers
in '72-'73 versus '14-'15.

00:23:28.920 --> 00:23:34.380
At the college level, 57% of
all college undergraduates

00:23:34.380 --> 00:23:35.460
are female.

00:23:35.460 --> 00:23:39.690
Only 43% of all
athletes are female.

00:23:39.690 --> 00:23:42.810
And same animal in terms
of more opportunities

00:23:42.810 --> 00:23:45.150
have been added for men
in the last 10 years

00:23:45.150 --> 00:23:47.250
than have been added for female.

00:23:47.250 --> 00:23:50.550
So instead of this
gap getting smaller,

00:23:50.550 --> 00:23:53.910
which it started to do in
the first 30 years or so,

00:23:53.910 --> 00:23:56.700
it's now starting
to peel apart again.

00:23:56.700 --> 00:24:00.480
So the gap is greater.

00:24:00.480 --> 00:24:02.250
So why is this happening?

00:24:02.250 --> 00:24:04.590
Right?

00:24:04.590 --> 00:24:06.720
As the wrestling
coaches will tell you,

00:24:06.720 --> 00:24:09.540
every time a wrestling
program is dropped

00:24:09.540 --> 00:24:12.540
it's because of Title IX.

00:24:12.540 --> 00:24:15.390
Men's sports are suffering
because of what's

00:24:15.390 --> 00:24:19.320
happening for women, with
women, and the answer

00:24:19.320 --> 00:24:21.290
is just the opposite.

00:24:21.290 --> 00:24:23.850
What is happening
is that men's sports

00:24:23.850 --> 00:24:25.920
are getting dropped
so that money

00:24:25.920 --> 00:24:31.530
can shift to fund the arms race
in football and basketball.

00:24:31.530 --> 00:24:34.350
And you can tell because
men have been growing

00:24:34.350 --> 00:24:38.220
more than women, and women
are still not close to equity,

00:24:38.220 --> 00:24:40.740
and nothing's been done
over the last 10 years.

00:24:40.740 --> 00:24:42.750
You can tell that's
true, but you can also

00:24:42.750 --> 00:24:44.160
tell from this chart.

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:49.200
If you look at that bright
yellow 328 up there,

00:24:49.200 --> 00:24:53.760
this shows you the net gain
and loss of sport programs

00:24:53.760 --> 00:24:55.440
for men and women.

00:24:55.440 --> 00:24:57.660
You can't just look
at drop programs.

00:24:57.660 --> 00:24:59.940
We add and drop
sports all the time.

00:24:59.940 --> 00:25:02.426
In the 70s women
didn't play soccer.

00:25:02.426 --> 00:25:04.050
Men didn't play soccer
in this country.

00:25:04.050 --> 00:25:06.030
We sure didn't play lacrosse.

00:25:06.030 --> 00:25:07.230
We were playing badminton.

00:25:07.230 --> 00:25:09.090
We we're playing field hockey.

00:25:09.090 --> 00:25:12.310
So sports change all the time.

00:25:12.310 --> 00:25:16.590
So you have to look at what
the net gains and losses are.

00:25:16.590 --> 00:25:20.700
So you can see that in women's
sports, it's always net gains.

00:25:20.700 --> 00:25:23.760
In men's sport, in Division
two and three, which

00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:26.760
are the least financially
supported sports,

00:25:26.760 --> 00:25:30.230
in Division two and three,
men's sports continue to grow.

00:25:30.230 --> 00:25:34.050
Division one, the richest
programs in the United States

00:25:34.050 --> 00:25:36.240
are the ones that
are dropping sports,

00:25:36.240 --> 00:25:39.810
and they're doing it
to fuel this arms race.

00:25:39.810 --> 00:25:43.920
If you look at the percentage
of the men's sport budgets

00:25:43.920 --> 00:25:47.280
that go to just
these two sports,

00:25:47.280 --> 00:25:50.910
and knowing that Division one is
the highest competitive level,

00:25:50.910 --> 00:25:54.890
you're looking at FBS, the
college football playoff,

00:25:54.890 --> 00:26:00.630
81% of the men's sports
budgets among these 125 FBS

00:26:00.630 --> 00:26:05.670
institutions, 81% percent
go to just those two sports.

00:26:05.670 --> 00:26:08.430
And the number that really
kills me on this chart

00:26:08.430 --> 00:26:13.570
is look at Division 1, no
football, third row down.

00:26:13.570 --> 00:26:15.910
Right, Division 1, no football.

00:26:15.910 --> 00:26:19.110
So there's no football
players, zero.

00:26:19.110 --> 00:26:21.790
There's just men's basketball.

00:26:21.790 --> 00:26:23.920
And men's basketball,
those 12 players

00:26:23.920 --> 00:26:27.430
are getting 44% of the
men's operating budget.

00:26:27.430 --> 00:26:32.380
So have no doubt that why this
is happening in terms of men's

00:26:32.380 --> 00:26:35.860
non-revenue sports
being dropped.

00:26:35.860 --> 00:26:38.920
This is a quick and dirty in
terms of the financial support

00:26:38.920 --> 00:26:41.600
of men's versus women's sports.

00:26:41.600 --> 00:26:43.940
Title IX does not
require equal dollars.

00:26:43.940 --> 00:26:45.070
It doesn't.

00:26:45.070 --> 00:26:48.970
But if you look at the money
picture, follow the money,

00:26:48.970 --> 00:26:52.970
you can see there's smoke
here, and where there's smoke,

00:26:52.970 --> 00:26:54.760
there's usually fire.

00:26:54.760 --> 00:26:59.980
And this gives you a good idea
of how poorly women's sports

00:26:59.980 --> 00:27:03.430
are still supported in
every single division.

00:27:03.430 --> 00:27:06.820
Yes, football is more
expensive than other sports,

00:27:06.820 --> 00:27:12.120
but when you look at
these of funding gaps--

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:16.270
I testify in Title IX
lawsuits all the time.

00:27:16.270 --> 00:27:18.520
Believe me, there are
very few institutions

00:27:18.520 --> 00:27:22.930
in this country that are in
compliance with Title IX.

00:27:22.930 --> 00:27:25.180
Media coverage of women's
sports-- and Mike Messner,

00:27:25.180 --> 00:27:28.700
I love Mike Messner, is going
to speak on this later on.

00:27:28.700 --> 00:27:31.390
So I'm not going to
spend time on this.

00:27:31.390 --> 00:27:35.890
But fortunately, we have--

00:27:35.890 --> 00:27:39.820
Mike, is it still true that
we are getting more coverage

00:27:39.820 --> 00:27:40.990
than the horses and dogs?

00:27:40.990 --> 00:27:43.460
[CHUCKLES]

00:27:43.460 --> 00:27:45.930
- Unless the horses
and dogs are being used

00:27:45.930 --> 00:27:47.420
to make fun of women's sports.

00:27:47.420 --> 00:27:48.390
- I got it.

00:27:48.390 --> 00:27:50.840
But seriously, horse
racing and dog racing

00:27:50.840 --> 00:27:52.580
used to be covered
more than women.

00:27:52.580 --> 00:27:57.290
I think we might
have surpassed that.

00:27:57.290 --> 00:28:00.895
Newspaper coverage is
a function of what does

00:28:00.895 --> 00:28:03.980
a sports editor want to see.

00:28:03.980 --> 00:28:07.130
What does the sports editor
want his writers to write about.

00:28:07.130 --> 00:28:09.530
Sports editors do
not take surveys

00:28:09.530 --> 00:28:12.200
and see what the public wants.

00:28:12.200 --> 00:28:14.926
So we don't have very
many women or people

00:28:14.926 --> 00:28:16.800
of color, for that
matter, in sports editors.

00:28:16.800 --> 00:28:18.590
You can see that
in our coverage.

00:28:18.590 --> 00:28:20.910
When you look at college
sports leadership,

00:28:20.910 --> 00:28:23.960
this is where the real
crimes are being wrought.

00:28:23.960 --> 00:28:28.437
You're looking at
roughly 80% of--

00:28:28.437 --> 00:28:30.020
I don't care whether
you pick coaches,

00:28:30.020 --> 00:28:33.560
athletic directors,
administrators, 80%

00:28:33.560 --> 00:28:35.330
are white males.

00:28:35.330 --> 00:28:37.370
And that's a large statement.

00:28:37.370 --> 00:28:40.340
But roughly, that's
about what it is.

00:28:40.340 --> 00:28:44.720
And these numbers are
worse for persons of color.

00:28:44.720 --> 00:28:49.160
So you can see that in
terms of employment,

00:28:49.160 --> 00:28:53.840
Title IX has not had a
concomitant effect on women

00:28:53.840 --> 00:28:55.460
in terms of employment.

00:28:55.460 --> 00:28:57.500
Now, the view from
ground zero, and I know

00:28:57.500 --> 00:29:00.020
you don't have glasses, OK so--

00:29:00.020 --> 00:29:01.610
and these are very
small numbers,

00:29:01.610 --> 00:29:04.100
but I want you to look
at the last column only.

00:29:04.100 --> 00:29:05.360
OK?

00:29:05.360 --> 00:29:11.330
This is the female participation
gap at each of the Ivy League

00:29:11.330 --> 00:29:13.280
institutions.

00:29:13.280 --> 00:29:17.990
So that is the number of women's
participation opportunities

00:29:17.990 --> 00:29:23.330
that need to be added
for women to comprise

00:29:23.330 --> 00:29:27.140
their percentage in these
respective student bodies.

00:29:27.140 --> 00:29:30.740
So I've kept men's
participation constant

00:29:30.740 --> 00:29:35.030
and just did a simple
mathematical formula.

00:29:35.030 --> 00:29:39.980
So as you can see,
Harvard is only 122

00:29:39.980 --> 00:29:44.780
shy in terms of
having to do something

00:29:44.780 --> 00:29:46.349
more for women's sports.

00:29:46.349 --> 00:29:48.140
So I'm here to tell
you that Harvard is not

00:29:48.140 --> 00:29:50.570
in compliance with Title IX.

00:29:50.570 --> 00:29:52.614
But why don't I end with that.

00:29:52.614 --> 00:29:56.486
[APPLAUSE]

00:29:56.486 --> 00:29:58.910
- Well done.

00:29:58.910 --> 00:29:59.960
- Thank you.

00:29:59.960 --> 00:30:01.290
Good morning.

00:30:01.290 --> 00:30:04.730
My name is Anita DeFrantz and
I come from points beyond.

00:30:04.730 --> 00:30:09.260
I was just in
Denmark where there

00:30:09.260 --> 00:30:12.680
was a gathering of all the
international federations

00:30:12.680 --> 00:30:15.380
of the world that are part
of the Olympic movement.

00:30:15.380 --> 00:30:19.100
And this is important to
us because, in many senses,

00:30:19.100 --> 00:30:22.970
the Olympic movement has
kept sports alive worldwide,

00:30:22.970 --> 00:30:24.440
not intentionally.

00:30:24.440 --> 00:30:29.120
And certainly, people know that
Pierre de Coubertin wasn't that

00:30:29.120 --> 00:30:30.620
much of a fan of women's sport.

00:30:30.620 --> 00:30:33.470
In fact, he's quoted as saying
that the purpose for women

00:30:33.470 --> 00:30:39.890
is to applaud politely the man
as they endeavor through sport.

00:30:39.890 --> 00:30:42.410
To his credit, he
never prohibited women

00:30:42.410 --> 00:30:43.160
from competing.

00:30:43.160 --> 00:30:44.900
He never put up a rope.

00:30:44.900 --> 00:30:47.750
He just did not support it much.

00:30:47.750 --> 00:30:49.700
I wanted you to
get a sense for how

00:30:49.700 --> 00:30:53.030
the Olympic movement has grown.

00:30:53.030 --> 00:30:54.980
Sports opportunities
have grown and I

00:30:54.980 --> 00:30:58.850
hope you can see it
better than I can.

00:30:58.850 --> 00:31:01.970
You'll see that in
the year 19,000,

00:31:01.970 --> 00:31:04.220
the number of sports
for women were two,

00:31:04.220 --> 00:31:06.610
the number of national
Olympic committees were five,

00:31:06.610 --> 00:31:09.770
and the number of
participants were 22.

00:31:09.770 --> 00:31:11.300
As you go down,
eventually you'll

00:31:11.300 --> 00:31:12.980
get to the Olympic
Winter sports,

00:31:12.980 --> 00:31:14.854
when that lighter color is--

00:31:14.854 --> 00:31:16.520
boy, that's really
hard for you to read.

00:31:16.520 --> 00:31:17.470
I'm sorry.

00:31:17.470 --> 00:31:19.340
The lighter color is
added, then you have

00:31:19.340 --> 00:31:21.260
both the Olympic Winter Games.

00:31:21.260 --> 00:31:24.470
Look at 1924, both
the Olympic Winter

00:31:24.470 --> 00:31:26.660
Games and the Olympic games.

00:31:26.660 --> 00:31:28.250
Very modest number.

00:31:28.250 --> 00:31:31.970
The men's numbers are not
that much more significantly,

00:31:31.970 --> 00:31:35.690
but over time, slowly but
surely we have more numbers,

00:31:35.690 --> 00:31:39.200
and that means across
the world, if we

00:31:39.200 --> 00:31:41.870
were to put up the numbers
of women competitors

00:31:41.870 --> 00:31:43.580
from the United
States, it would be

00:31:43.580 --> 00:31:47.870
much larger than any other
country, for which I am proud.

00:31:47.870 --> 00:31:51.110
I then learned that
by the year 2000

00:31:51.110 --> 00:31:54.320
there were fewer than 2000 women
who had represented the United

00:31:54.320 --> 00:31:57.890
States at the Olympic games,
which is such a tiny number.

00:31:57.890 --> 00:32:01.760
The numbers will get larger
because we needed to do that.

00:32:01.760 --> 00:32:04.790
Still, this gives you a
snapshot of the numbers

00:32:04.790 --> 00:32:10.730
of women competing at the games
throughout modern time, which

00:32:10.730 --> 00:32:13.320
for us, started in 1900.

00:32:13.320 --> 00:32:15.500
Now this one-- percentage
is also important.

00:32:15.500 --> 00:32:17.840
The percentage of
events for women because

00:32:17.840 --> 00:32:22.280
at a certain point women had a
better chance at winning medals

00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:25.370
than men did, mathematically,
because there were actually

00:32:25.370 --> 00:32:28.160
more events for women,
and a smaller number

00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:30.920
of women competing,
and that helped

00:32:30.920 --> 00:32:32.820
the national Olympic
committee to recognize

00:32:32.820 --> 00:32:35.300
that they could be more
successful if only they

00:32:35.300 --> 00:32:38.060
were to support their women,
and they could go home

00:32:38.060 --> 00:32:39.410
with more medals.

00:32:39.410 --> 00:32:41.780
Now, I didn't announce
this too loudly,

00:32:41.780 --> 00:32:45.710
but we kept putting the numbers
up, and they finally got that.

00:32:45.710 --> 00:32:50.200
And indeed, you'll note
starting in at least 19--

00:32:50.200 --> 00:32:55.280
I'm sorry, starting
in 2008, '12, and '16,

00:32:55.280 --> 00:32:58.490
many of the larger teams
had more women than men.

00:32:58.490 --> 00:33:02.630
And Indeed, the mighty
nation Bhutan had no men,

00:33:02.630 --> 00:33:06.950
but only had women on their
Olympic team in Rio de Janeiro.

00:33:06.950 --> 00:33:09.230
You start seeing that
there is a recognition

00:33:09.230 --> 00:33:13.850
that your country can be made
proud by having women athletes.

00:33:13.850 --> 00:33:18.230
When one of the goals of
the IOC, since our Congress

00:33:18.230 --> 00:33:20.910
in 1994--

00:33:20.910 --> 00:33:24.140
Congress means we bring together
not just this International

00:33:24.140 --> 00:33:27.820
Olympic Committee, our annual
meeting is called the Session.

00:33:27.820 --> 00:33:31.640
But we bring together along
with IOC members, the National

00:33:31.640 --> 00:33:33.630
Olympic Committee members.

00:33:33.630 --> 00:33:36.170
There are now 206 National
Olympic Committee members.

00:33:36.170 --> 00:33:37.610
That's more members
than there are

00:33:37.610 --> 00:33:39.500
members of the United Nation.

00:33:39.500 --> 00:33:43.160
In part because Puerto Rico
has its own National Olympic

00:33:43.160 --> 00:33:45.500
Committee and others who
would not necessarily

00:33:45.500 --> 00:33:48.890
be recognized by the UN
as separate countries.

00:33:48.890 --> 00:33:52.490
So there are more NOCs
than there are countries

00:33:52.490 --> 00:33:54.530
for historical reasons.

00:33:54.530 --> 00:33:59.660
And we also, for the games
in Rio, created something

00:33:59.660 --> 00:34:02.010
called the refugee team.

00:34:02.010 --> 00:34:04.790
We recognized that there
are people in these refugee

00:34:04.790 --> 00:34:07.560
camps, some of whom have
been there for decades,

00:34:07.560 --> 00:34:09.909
and we wanted the
young people who've

00:34:09.909 --> 00:34:12.000
grown up there to have a
chance to be Olympians.

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:12.500
[APPLAUSE]

00:34:12.500 --> 00:34:17.897
So the first ever refugee
team competed in Rio.

00:34:17.897 --> 00:34:19.730
And by the way, we don't
just say OK, great.

00:34:19.730 --> 00:34:20.479
Thanks for coming.

00:34:20.479 --> 00:34:22.880
You competed, you did well, bye.

00:34:22.880 --> 00:34:24.889
We stay with those
members of the team.

00:34:24.889 --> 00:34:26.660
We help them get placed.

00:34:26.660 --> 00:34:28.159
We help them develop
the skills they

00:34:28.159 --> 00:34:31.130
need to get back into
society and some of them

00:34:31.130 --> 00:34:33.230
are continuing to compete.

00:34:33.230 --> 00:34:35.630
So moving on, I wanted
you to see the overall--

00:34:38.330 --> 00:34:39.480
the curve.

00:34:39.480 --> 00:34:44.540
And you'll see that the men are
continually on an upward swing,

00:34:44.540 --> 00:34:47.179
but that's the total number
of athletes at the games.

00:34:47.179 --> 00:34:51.920
And the women start to
go up, and up, and up.

00:34:51.920 --> 00:34:56.030
Just quickly, from
1900 to 1984, there

00:34:56.030 --> 00:34:59.970
were about 12,000 women who
competed at the Olympic games.

00:34:59.970 --> 00:35:03.300
From 1988 to 2016,
there have been

00:35:03.300 --> 00:35:06.330
over 30,000 women who have
competed at the Olympic games.

00:35:06.330 --> 00:35:09.240
Which to me, says that there
is a large cadre of women

00:35:09.240 --> 00:35:13.680
available to give back, who
are of the proper age group

00:35:13.680 --> 00:35:16.410
to be able to give
their time, and take

00:35:16.410 --> 00:35:18.300
on positions of leadership.

00:35:18.300 --> 00:35:21.670
The IOC has made it
clear that we believe--

00:35:21.670 --> 00:35:23.700
if you can believe
that we believe this--

00:35:23.700 --> 00:35:28.140
that the world is made
up of at least 50% women,

00:35:28.140 --> 00:35:31.170
probably more, but
at least 50% women,

00:35:31.170 --> 00:35:33.750
and therefore the number
of athletes at the games

00:35:33.750 --> 00:35:37.020
should reflect the
world, and the number

00:35:37.020 --> 00:35:39.480
of positions in
leadership should likewise

00:35:39.480 --> 00:35:41.201
reflect the world.

00:35:41.201 --> 00:35:43.200
Studies have been done
throughout the world that

00:35:43.200 --> 00:35:45.900
show that boards of
directors that are equally

00:35:45.900 --> 00:35:50.850
made up of women and men,
what a shock, equality means--

00:35:50.850 --> 00:35:54.520
none of this equity
stuff for me, equality.

00:35:54.520 --> 00:35:57.360
Those boards do
a much better job

00:35:57.360 --> 00:35:59.430
of leading their organizations.

00:35:59.430 --> 00:36:02.400
They're much more successful
than other boards.

00:36:02.400 --> 00:36:05.460
So if you know of any boards
they are predominantly made up

00:36:05.460 --> 00:36:08.024
of one sex other than
the other, you can just

00:36:08.024 --> 00:36:10.440
tell them they would do better
if they would get their act

00:36:10.440 --> 00:36:11.850
together and even it out.

00:36:11.850 --> 00:36:13.347
It's all for the better.

00:36:13.347 --> 00:36:14.430
That's what we want to do.

00:36:14.430 --> 00:36:17.110
We want to make things better.

00:36:17.110 --> 00:36:21.330
So, you can see from this chart
that slowly, far too slowly,

00:36:21.330 --> 00:36:26.520
but certainly, we're
moving towards equality

00:36:26.520 --> 00:36:27.810
at the Olympic games.

00:36:27.810 --> 00:36:29.100
One other thing that happened.

00:36:29.100 --> 00:36:31.530
As we move towards
more equality,

00:36:31.530 --> 00:36:36.220
we noticed that the reporting
at the Olympic games

00:36:36.220 --> 00:36:37.800
became proportionate.

00:36:37.800 --> 00:36:39.990
In other words, if
your team was made up

00:36:39.990 --> 00:36:45.450
of 40% men and 60% women,
the reporting on the games

00:36:45.450 --> 00:36:50.820
was made up of 60% women
stories and 40% male stories.

00:36:50.820 --> 00:36:53.000
I don't know how the
journalists do that,

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:56.910
but it followed that trend,
which is even more compelling

00:36:56.910 --> 00:36:59.650
to have equal numbers of
athletes, men and women

00:36:59.650 --> 00:37:03.990
in the game so we can get
equal number of reporting.

00:37:03.990 --> 00:37:08.010
And the remarkable thing is
they can do it for two weeks

00:37:08.010 --> 00:37:09.630
during the games.

00:37:09.630 --> 00:37:11.490
I think you can
probably do it forever

00:37:11.490 --> 00:37:12.930
if you really wanted to.

00:37:12.930 --> 00:37:13.980
It works.

00:37:13.980 --> 00:37:16.860
So we need to get
people understanding

00:37:16.860 --> 00:37:19.200
that it does work
and the world will

00:37:19.200 --> 00:37:22.780
be a better place when we get
more of the stories out there.

00:37:22.780 --> 00:37:25.590
OK, the next slide has
to do with the new sports

00:37:25.590 --> 00:37:27.060
on the program.

00:37:27.060 --> 00:37:28.890
There are new sports
on the program

00:37:28.890 --> 00:37:31.710
and that is one messed up chart.

00:37:31.710 --> 00:37:33.070
I'm sorry.

00:37:33.070 --> 00:37:38.640
Where it says year, just put
the zero over so it's 1900.

00:37:38.640 --> 00:37:43.129
1994, things like that.

00:37:43.129 --> 00:37:43.920
So you can do that.

00:37:43.920 --> 00:37:46.050
You guys are at Radcliffe.

00:37:46.050 --> 00:37:49.380
You can move the
chart, move the column.

00:37:49.380 --> 00:37:51.930
And you see how long it took
to get some of the sports

00:37:51.930 --> 00:37:54.170
on the programme, which
is really amazing.

00:37:54.170 --> 00:37:57.570
1976, which were
the great games--

00:37:57.570 --> 00:37:58.780
yes, that's when I competed.

00:37:58.780 --> 00:37:59.780
There we go.

00:37:59.780 --> 00:38:01.980
1976, go!

00:38:01.980 --> 00:38:03.930
Yeah!

00:38:03.930 --> 00:38:06.112
Finally, rowing, basketball.

00:38:06.112 --> 00:38:08.070
Did you realize that
women's basketball was not

00:38:08.070 --> 00:38:12.240
on the program of the
Olympic games until 1976?

00:38:12.240 --> 00:38:15.240
Then it goes much faster as
we move along from that point

00:38:15.240 --> 00:38:18.300
and the games in London
was the first games when

00:38:18.300 --> 00:38:21.140
all the sports on the
program had women's events.

00:38:21.140 --> 00:38:23.350
It took us from--

00:38:23.350 --> 00:38:31.140
let's see, 1896 to 2012
to get all of the sports

00:38:31.140 --> 00:38:34.960
on the program for
men, for women.

00:38:34.960 --> 00:38:37.770
It's often pointed out to
me that men do not take part

00:38:37.770 --> 00:38:39.750
in synchronized swimming.

00:38:39.750 --> 00:38:40.530
Not true.

00:38:40.530 --> 00:38:45.300
At the Fino World Championships,
it was a mixed event.

00:38:45.300 --> 00:38:49.290
And the gentleman who all
those many years ago complained

00:38:49.290 --> 00:38:51.630
bitterly that he was
not allowed to compete,

00:38:51.630 --> 00:38:54.270
his duet actually won
the world championships

00:38:54.270 --> 00:38:57.510
in mixed synchronized swimming.

00:38:57.510 --> 00:39:01.500
I've lost his name, but I'm sure
Twitter, Google, or somebody

00:39:01.500 --> 00:39:03.880
can find his name for you.

00:39:03.880 --> 00:39:07.680
So, yes, synchronized
swimming has found its way

00:39:07.680 --> 00:39:11.670
to making opportunities
for men and women.

00:39:11.670 --> 00:39:13.710
It's important to
know that there are

00:39:13.710 --> 00:39:16.000
sports that continue to go on.

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:19.780
In the Olympic
Winter Games we were

00:39:19.780 --> 00:39:23.200
coming very close to parity,
then new sports came on,

00:39:23.200 --> 00:39:25.720
and I will confess I was
asleep at the switch.

00:39:25.720 --> 00:39:28.780
I was no longer in charge of
the Women and Sports Commission

00:39:28.780 --> 00:39:33.760
and what happened was a lot
of these new sports came on,

00:39:33.760 --> 00:39:35.470
and nobody was
reminding them that you

00:39:35.470 --> 00:39:38.620
have to have equal numbers
of women athletes and men

00:39:38.620 --> 00:39:39.670
athletes.

00:39:39.670 --> 00:39:42.130
And they didn't because
unfortunately, guys

00:39:42.130 --> 00:39:44.650
were in charge again,
and guys do what they do.

00:39:44.650 --> 00:39:47.080
They say OK, let's have
a lot more guys here.

00:39:47.080 --> 00:39:49.360
Oh, women, let's
have some women.

00:39:49.360 --> 00:39:51.640
These are new sports
so who's going

00:39:51.640 --> 00:39:54.400
to notice that we have
twice as many men as women.

00:39:54.400 --> 00:39:56.420
Well, after the fact I noticed.

00:39:56.420 --> 00:39:59.740
So it's going to take us a
while to get back to equality

00:39:59.740 --> 00:40:02.590
at the Olympic Winter Games
because of one set of games

00:40:02.590 --> 00:40:07.390
where they put 20 men in and
only 10 women in the sport

00:40:07.390 --> 00:40:09.410
of say, border cross.

00:40:09.410 --> 00:40:11.830
You all know what
border cross is.

00:40:11.830 --> 00:40:17.270
And I'm not making a
political comment on this.

00:40:17.270 --> 00:40:18.430
It's a lot of fun.

00:40:18.430 --> 00:40:23.410
You line up four skiers at the
top of essentially moguls hill

00:40:23.410 --> 00:40:26.530
and they race to get across
to the finish line first,

00:40:26.530 --> 00:40:29.150
often bumping into one
another along the way,

00:40:29.150 --> 00:40:31.090
making it exciting to
see who will make it

00:40:31.090 --> 00:40:33.190
to the finish line.

00:40:33.190 --> 00:40:36.137
But that sport-- how many
women really why do that?

00:40:36.137 --> 00:40:36.970
Well, I'll tell you.

00:40:36.970 --> 00:40:38.860
A lot of women want to do that.

00:40:38.860 --> 00:40:40.510
It's fun.

00:40:40.510 --> 00:40:43.180
But not so many got the
chance at the games.

00:40:43.180 --> 00:40:45.790
All right, now I do
have to hurry along.

00:40:45.790 --> 00:40:46.990
The last games.

00:40:46.990 --> 00:40:49.900
What we do at the IOC
is we pay attention.

00:40:49.900 --> 00:40:52.360
You'll see here, if you can't
see it, that we pay attention

00:40:52.360 --> 00:40:54.670
not only to the number
of athletes there,

00:40:54.670 --> 00:40:57.389
but we pay attention to the
National Olympic Committees

00:40:57.389 --> 00:40:59.680
and whether or not they have
women in their leadership.

00:40:59.680 --> 00:41:02.320
Where they have
women, [INAUDIBLE] who

00:41:02.320 --> 00:41:05.010
is the person in charge
of the team at the games,

00:41:05.010 --> 00:41:07.780
where they have women as
flag bearers and where

00:41:07.780 --> 00:41:10.450
they have accredited media.

00:41:10.450 --> 00:41:12.760
We're looking at the
numbers because if you

00:41:12.760 --> 00:41:14.680
watch the numbers,
you can see if things

00:41:14.680 --> 00:41:18.310
are going that direction we
say we want them to go or not.

00:41:18.310 --> 00:41:21.460
We are paying attention to
how the games are presented.

00:41:21.460 --> 00:41:24.250
We're paying attention
to who gets to be there

00:41:24.250 --> 00:41:28.060
and what their experiences
are at the games.

00:41:28.060 --> 00:41:33.130
This has been a very
fast overview of a very--

00:41:33.130 --> 00:41:37.870
complicated is not the right
word, but confusing might be.

00:41:37.870 --> 00:41:40.150
The way the Olympic
movement is structured,

00:41:40.150 --> 00:41:41.650
the International
Olympic Committee

00:41:41.650 --> 00:41:43.600
owns the Olympic games.

00:41:43.600 --> 00:41:45.460
We're the only ones
who can say, yes,

00:41:45.460 --> 00:41:48.070
this is where the
Olympic games will be.

00:41:48.070 --> 00:41:51.400
The IOC decides what sports
will be on the program,

00:41:51.400 --> 00:41:55.030
but the International
Federations control the sports.

00:41:55.030 --> 00:41:57.100
The National Olympic
Committees are the ones

00:41:57.100 --> 00:41:58.210
who enter the athletes.

00:42:00.730 --> 00:42:04.740
It's often said that
there's three pillars

00:42:04.740 --> 00:42:05.740
of the Olympic movement.

00:42:05.740 --> 00:42:07.270
Well, I think there
are four, and I

00:42:07.270 --> 00:42:11.780
prefer the pyramid, which oddly
enough has four sides to it.

00:42:11.780 --> 00:42:13.670
We think of a pyramid
and the triangle,

00:42:13.670 --> 00:42:15.050
but it has four sides.

00:42:15.050 --> 00:42:17.760
So I think the athletes
are a very essential part

00:42:17.760 --> 00:42:19.750
of the Olympic movement.

00:42:19.750 --> 00:42:20.840
We have to have athletes.

00:42:20.840 --> 00:42:22.270
We have to have
International Federations.

00:42:22.270 --> 00:42:24.095
We have to have National
Olympic Committees

00:42:24.095 --> 00:42:25.970
and we have to have the
International Olympic

00:42:25.970 --> 00:42:30.760
Committee, or sports would
exist, but the others would not

00:42:30.760 --> 00:42:34.247
without the International
Olympic Committee.

00:42:34.247 --> 00:42:35.830
I'm sure they'll be
lots of questions.

00:42:35.830 --> 00:42:39.460
I've spoken a lot of Olympic
languages with alphabet soup

00:42:39.460 --> 00:42:41.794
and I hope that you'll be
able to remember the questions

00:42:41.794 --> 00:42:44.209
because you're going to hear
a lot more interesting things

00:42:44.209 --> 00:42:45.280
than I have to offer.

00:42:45.280 --> 00:42:47.890
Bottom line, we had Title IX.

00:42:47.890 --> 00:42:52.210
How on earth did women get to
the starting lines in countries

00:42:52.210 --> 00:42:54.520
throughout the world that
didn't have Title IX?

00:42:54.520 --> 00:42:57.040
In part, the NCAA
helped that greatly

00:42:57.040 --> 00:43:01.230
to get women to the line,
but it is really miraculous.

00:43:01.230 --> 00:43:06.280
And through the determination of
other women like Alice Milliat,

00:43:06.280 --> 00:43:08.950
who is a French woman who
in the 1920s made sure

00:43:08.950 --> 00:43:11.980
that women had track and field.

00:43:11.980 --> 00:43:13.420
They called it athletics.

00:43:13.420 --> 00:43:16.570
track and Field, and she put on
track and field events that had

00:43:16.570 --> 00:43:20.920
20,000 spectators, which
is why you see in 1928,

00:43:20.920 --> 00:43:24.460
track and field coming onto the
Olympic program in the way it

00:43:24.460 --> 00:43:27.070
should have back in the 1900's.

00:43:27.070 --> 00:43:30.370
And with one minute and
22 seconds left, oops 20,

00:43:30.370 --> 00:43:31.738
I will end my presentation.

00:43:31.738 --> 00:43:32.238
Thank you.

00:43:32.238 --> 00:43:34.190
[APPLAUSE]

00:43:38.100 --> 00:43:38.850
- OK.

00:43:38.850 --> 00:43:40.800
I'm going to stay here
and do my presentation

00:43:40.800 --> 00:43:44.335
because you guys wouldn't be
able to see me over there.

00:43:44.335 --> 00:43:46.800
So I'm kind of rounding
everything up and talking

00:43:46.800 --> 00:43:48.810
about disability
and how disability

00:43:48.810 --> 00:43:51.690
plays into who gets to play.

00:43:51.690 --> 00:43:54.360
And I come at this from a couple
of different perspectives,

00:43:54.360 --> 00:43:55.943
three different
perspectives actually,

00:43:55.943 --> 00:43:57.927
as I go through my presentation.

00:43:57.927 --> 00:43:59.760
So the first is kind a
landscape of where we

00:43:59.760 --> 00:44:02.400
are with just disability sport.

00:44:02.400 --> 00:44:05.100
I think it's really relevant
and important to talk about that

00:44:05.100 --> 00:44:06.630
before I move onto
the gender piece,

00:44:06.630 --> 00:44:09.780
because they intersect and
they do play into one another.

00:44:09.780 --> 00:44:12.240
And I'll talk a little bit
about the role that gender plays

00:44:12.240 --> 00:44:14.490
in disability sports,
and then wrap it up

00:44:14.490 --> 00:44:17.340
with a current example
of this question of who

00:44:17.340 --> 00:44:19.140
gets to play, where
do they get the play,

00:44:19.140 --> 00:44:23.480
and what's the structure
around them getting to play.

00:44:23.480 --> 00:44:25.600
All right, so, to start
out with where we are,

00:44:25.600 --> 00:44:28.260
I'm not going to bore you
guys with too much relevant US

00:44:28.260 --> 00:44:30.600
law and case law, but I
think the biggest thing

00:44:30.600 --> 00:44:33.310
to understand with that is--

00:44:33.310 --> 00:44:36.570
and I know Anita talks about
this a lot in her presentations

00:44:36.570 --> 00:44:40.440
and what she believes as far
as sport being a human right,

00:44:40.440 --> 00:44:42.300
and who's allowed to play.

00:44:42.300 --> 00:44:44.910
Well, as you guys can see
through some of this US law

00:44:44.910 --> 00:44:47.340
and case law, for
the longest time

00:44:47.340 --> 00:44:50.220
it's been a privilege for
individuals with disabilities

00:44:50.220 --> 00:44:51.660
to be able to play sport.

00:44:51.660 --> 00:44:52.662
It has not been a right.

00:44:52.662 --> 00:44:55.120
And so the only way that they've
been able to access sport,

00:44:55.120 --> 00:44:57.450
that we have been
able to access sport,

00:44:57.450 --> 00:45:00.150
is through law
that you see here.

00:45:00.150 --> 00:45:01.980
Relevant US law,
Title IX, Rehab Act,

00:45:01.980 --> 00:45:06.480
which Donna spoke about in
her presentation, the ADA.

00:45:06.480 --> 00:45:10.140
And in relevant case law with
Casey Martin vs. the PGA,

00:45:10.140 --> 00:45:12.810
McFadden vs. Cousins, which
is Tatiana McFadden, who's

00:45:12.810 --> 00:45:16.460
a pretty well-known
female racer right now.

00:45:16.460 --> 00:45:18.060
And so those are
the opportunities

00:45:18.060 --> 00:45:21.870
that we have had to sort of
assert our right to play sport

00:45:21.870 --> 00:45:24.410
and our right to get
to the line, basically.

00:45:24.410 --> 00:45:27.090
That's how we as individuals
with disabilities

00:45:27.090 --> 00:45:29.230
get to the starting
line, quite often,

00:45:29.230 --> 00:45:32.250
is it has to be through
relevant case law.

00:45:32.250 --> 00:45:34.890
The last two pieces, and more
importantly the last piece,

00:45:34.890 --> 00:45:38.010
the OCR "Dear Colleague
Letter" of 2013,

00:45:38.010 --> 00:45:39.960
that's been one of the
most important pieces

00:45:39.960 --> 00:45:42.180
of clarification
and legislation that

00:45:42.180 --> 00:45:46.320
moved our opportunity the
most for that I've seen,

00:45:46.320 --> 00:45:48.990
in the past probably
10 to 15 years.

00:45:48.990 --> 00:45:52.620
And basically, what that is was
a clarification of section 504

00:45:52.620 --> 00:45:54.240
for the Rehab Act.

00:45:54.240 --> 00:45:57.150
Stating that you do have
to provide extra curricular

00:45:57.150 --> 00:46:00.240
opportunities for your
students with disabilities

00:46:00.240 --> 00:46:01.090
in your schools.

00:46:01.090 --> 00:46:03.450
And so it's a clarification
of that saying

00:46:03.450 --> 00:46:04.680
this is what you have to do.

00:46:07.380 --> 00:46:10.580
OK, so along with
that kind of privilege

00:46:10.580 --> 00:46:11.990
by having to go
through case law,

00:46:11.990 --> 00:46:14.000
and having to go
through US law, we

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:16.310
talk a lot about
who gets to make it

00:46:16.310 --> 00:46:19.220
to international and
professional opportunities

00:46:19.220 --> 00:46:20.330
to play sport.

00:46:20.330 --> 00:46:22.314
On the left you have
able-bodied individuals.

00:46:22.314 --> 00:46:24.480
They kind of have this
defined path of where you go.

00:46:24.480 --> 00:46:26.156
Play at recreational
level, youth

00:46:26.156 --> 00:46:28.280
sport level, scholastic,
intercollegiate, national,

00:46:28.280 --> 00:46:29.710
international, professional.

00:46:29.710 --> 00:46:33.680
It's a pretty linear progression
for able-bodied individuals

00:46:33.680 --> 00:46:35.240
to get there.

00:46:35.240 --> 00:46:37.700
On the right side, you have
people with a disability

00:46:37.700 --> 00:46:42.230
and we have play and recreation
level to some extent.

00:46:42.230 --> 00:46:44.090
That's more your
interscholastic level

00:46:44.090 --> 00:46:46.160
where you have
opportunities for PE

00:46:46.160 --> 00:46:49.130
or you have
opportunities outside

00:46:49.130 --> 00:46:51.555
of school for those
extracurricular activities.

00:46:51.555 --> 00:46:53.180
They're not completely
there right now.

00:46:53.180 --> 00:46:54.763
They're moving in
the right direction,

00:46:54.763 --> 00:46:57.950
but there is some
opportunity that exist there.

00:46:57.950 --> 00:47:00.170
Youth and sport level,
there are youth sports

00:47:00.170 --> 00:47:02.930
level opportunities for
kids with disabilities

00:47:02.930 --> 00:47:05.430
to play sport, depending
upon the sport.

00:47:05.430 --> 00:47:08.990
Scholastic, that's more
of your high school.

00:47:08.990 --> 00:47:12.050
Not a lot of that exists
outside of special recreation

00:47:12.050 --> 00:47:16.160
opportunities, special
recreation associations.

00:47:16.160 --> 00:47:17.930
You don't see a
lot of students who

00:47:17.930 --> 00:47:20.099
get to compete for
their high school.

00:47:20.099 --> 00:47:22.640
You see it-- and this is where
some of that relevant case law

00:47:22.640 --> 00:47:24.026
comes into play.

00:47:24.026 --> 00:47:25.400
You get to see
it, on some level,

00:47:25.400 --> 00:47:28.490
in individual sports
where students

00:47:28.490 --> 00:47:29.750
have been awarded the right--

00:47:29.750 --> 00:47:31.940
the right and the
privilege to be

00:47:31.940 --> 00:47:34.820
able to compete on their
track teams and earn

00:47:34.820 --> 00:47:36.012
points for their teams.

00:47:36.012 --> 00:47:37.970
And they go to state and
national competitions,

00:47:37.970 --> 00:47:39.428
or the right to
practice with them.

00:47:39.428 --> 00:47:40.880
You see it in swimming a bit.

00:47:40.880 --> 00:47:43.490
Where you see the hole
is in team competitions.

00:47:43.490 --> 00:47:45.050
And later on in the
presentation I'll

00:47:45.050 --> 00:47:47.060
talk a little bit about
that differentiation

00:47:47.060 --> 00:47:48.710
and what that looks like.

00:47:48.710 --> 00:47:50.882
Intercollegiate, another
huge hole exists.

00:47:50.882 --> 00:47:52.340
Again, later on in
the presentation

00:47:52.340 --> 00:47:54.230
I'll come back and
address that a little bit.

00:47:54.230 --> 00:47:55.730
And then international
professional.

00:47:55.730 --> 00:47:57.410
That's actually
far more developed

00:47:57.410 --> 00:48:00.200
than we see at the national
intercollegiate level

00:48:00.200 --> 00:48:03.020
with the Paralympic games,
with professional opportunities

00:48:03.020 --> 00:48:05.570
to play sports, team
sports actually,

00:48:05.570 --> 00:48:08.354
and the opportunity to be
professional swimmers, racers,

00:48:08.354 --> 00:48:10.020
and that kind of thing
across the world.

00:48:10.020 --> 00:48:12.290
So who makes it to here?

00:48:12.290 --> 00:48:14.110
We can all make it
to there, but there's

00:48:14.110 --> 00:48:17.690
significant gaps in our
ability to be able to play

00:48:17.690 --> 00:48:19.160
at those different levels.

00:48:19.160 --> 00:48:21.602
Just to kind of make this
tangible and show examples.

00:48:21.602 --> 00:48:23.060
At the University
of Illinois we're

00:48:23.060 --> 00:48:25.610
really fortunate to have
a pretty robust disability

00:48:25.610 --> 00:48:26.780
support program.

00:48:26.780 --> 00:48:31.370
And our student athletes achieve
at a very, very high level,

00:48:31.370 --> 00:48:33.920
winning championships,
winning races.

00:48:33.920 --> 00:48:36.560
What we think of as achieving
on the athletic side.

00:48:36.560 --> 00:48:38.600
And our student athletes,
when they come back

00:48:38.600 --> 00:48:41.480
from an international
competition,

00:48:41.480 --> 00:48:45.780
winning, succeeding,
there's zero recognition.

00:48:45.780 --> 00:48:48.740
There's zero support
from athletics

00:48:48.740 --> 00:48:51.140
from my university
in the same way

00:48:51.140 --> 00:48:53.657
that you would see their
able-bodied peers received at.

00:48:53.657 --> 00:48:55.740
We have had teams that won
national championships.

00:48:55.740 --> 00:49:00.260
We come back and it's just null.

00:49:00.260 --> 00:49:02.380
Mentioning Tatiana
McFadden earlier.

00:49:02.380 --> 00:49:05.730
Her legend is growing, and it's
getting bigger, and bigger,

00:49:05.730 --> 00:49:06.230
and bigger.

00:49:06.230 --> 00:49:07.610
And those of you
in the Boston area

00:49:07.610 --> 00:49:09.360
will get to see that
in a couple of weeks.

00:49:09.360 --> 00:49:14.000
But she was a student athlete on
our campus for a very long time

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:17.465
before she made this
transition into being

00:49:17.465 --> 00:49:18.710
a professional athlete.

00:49:18.710 --> 00:49:20.810
And the way I kind of
conceive and think of this

00:49:20.810 --> 00:49:24.540
is who wouldn't want her to
represent their university?

00:49:24.540 --> 00:49:25.040
Right?

00:49:25.040 --> 00:49:28.036
And who wouldn't want any
of our student athletes

00:49:28.036 --> 00:49:30.410
wearing Illinois, or wearing
Harvard, or wearing whatever

00:49:30.410 --> 00:49:32.390
school that might be across
their chest because they're

00:49:32.390 --> 00:49:34.340
such great representatives
of your university

00:49:34.340 --> 00:49:37.760
or of your high school
where those gaps exists.

00:49:37.760 --> 00:49:39.260
They train in the
exact same way.

00:49:39.260 --> 00:49:42.590
They compete in
the exact same way.

00:49:42.590 --> 00:49:47.840
That gap exists there and it's a
gap that we're looking to fill.

00:49:47.840 --> 00:49:51.256
Just looking at-- based off
that last little chart, when

00:49:51.256 --> 00:49:52.880
we talk about being
otherwise qualified

00:49:52.880 --> 00:49:55.860
to participate in all of
these levels of competition,

00:49:55.860 --> 00:49:58.730
what we're basically talking
about is skill and talent.

00:49:58.730 --> 00:50:01.790
You meet certain criteria
of age, or of gender

00:50:01.790 --> 00:50:07.160
or of classification level,
whatever it might be.

00:50:07.160 --> 00:50:09.940
But then we have this
otherwise qualified caveat,

00:50:09.940 --> 00:50:12.450
and that equals skill, and
it narrows as you get higher.

00:50:12.450 --> 00:50:14.450
You have to have a higher
level skill as you get

00:50:14.450 --> 00:50:16.250
higher and higher on the chart.

00:50:16.250 --> 00:50:17.780
And for athletes
with disabilities,

00:50:17.780 --> 00:50:20.360
you don't move up this chart
just because you're disabled.

00:50:20.360 --> 00:50:22.490
You don't move up this
sort of progression

00:50:22.490 --> 00:50:24.576
just because you
happen to be somebody

00:50:24.576 --> 00:50:26.450
that has a disability
that live in this area.

00:50:26.450 --> 00:50:28.100
You have to have skill.

00:50:28.100 --> 00:50:30.317
It's an intentional way for
you to get to that point.

00:50:30.317 --> 00:50:32.900
And so it's really important to
understand those two parallels

00:50:32.900 --> 00:50:37.229
between how able-bodied
athletes rise to that pinnacle

00:50:37.229 --> 00:50:38.645
and how athletes
with disabilities

00:50:38.645 --> 00:50:39.561
rise to that pinnacle.

00:50:42.410 --> 00:50:43.940
Just to kind of
touch on and go back

00:50:43.940 --> 00:50:46.070
to the case law a
little bit, there

00:50:46.070 --> 00:50:47.762
is a growing demand
for participation,

00:50:47.762 --> 00:50:49.220
and that's the
question that we get

00:50:49.220 --> 00:50:50.770
a lot is who's going to play?

00:50:50.770 --> 00:50:52.511
Where's the critical mass?

00:50:52.511 --> 00:50:54.260
Where are the athletes
that are demanding?

00:50:54.260 --> 00:50:55.740
Well, it's there.

00:50:55.740 --> 00:50:58.610
We kind of have our outliers of
people like Tatiana McFadden,

00:50:58.610 --> 00:51:01.005
or when you look in
the Olympic games

00:51:01.005 --> 00:51:02.630
with like a Natalie
Du Toit or somebody

00:51:02.630 --> 00:51:05.060
like that, who has competed
with a disability at both

00:51:05.060 --> 00:51:06.460
the Olympic and
Paralympic level.

00:51:06.460 --> 00:51:08.210
You have these outliers,
and while they're

00:51:08.210 --> 00:51:10.820
great to sort of start
the conversation,

00:51:10.820 --> 00:51:12.080
they don't sustain.

00:51:12.080 --> 00:51:15.680
Critical mass is what sustains
competition at a higher level,

00:51:15.680 --> 00:51:17.390
and so there are
student athletes that

00:51:17.390 --> 00:51:22.727
are demanding equal treatment
as varsity athletes, excuse me.

00:51:22.727 --> 00:51:24.560
It's through those
administrative complaints

00:51:24.560 --> 00:51:26.181
and lawsuits.

00:51:26.181 --> 00:51:27.680
Athletes with
disabilities are going

00:51:27.680 --> 00:51:30.350
to impact a greater demand
for similar opportunities

00:51:30.350 --> 00:51:33.560
at the collegiate level, where
we're beginning to see that now

00:51:33.560 --> 00:51:34.741
as we move forward.

00:51:34.741 --> 00:51:36.740
And then I think as this
generation's coming up,

00:51:36.740 --> 00:51:38.895
they're going to be more
expectant of equality,

00:51:38.895 --> 00:51:40.520
and they're going to
know their rights,

00:51:40.520 --> 00:51:42.410
and they're going to
know that this is not

00:51:42.410 --> 00:51:44.743
a privilege for them to be
able to participate in sport.

00:51:44.743 --> 00:51:47.117
It is their right.

00:51:47.117 --> 00:51:48.700
This is kind of where
we start to move

00:51:48.700 --> 00:51:49.600
a little bit into gender.

00:51:49.600 --> 00:51:51.725
I'm going to talk a little
bit about what the needs

00:51:51.725 --> 00:51:54.114
and barriers are with
athletes with disabilities,

00:51:54.114 --> 00:51:56.530
but it's going to bleed a
little bit into gender because I

00:51:56.530 --> 00:51:58.236
think the two are very similar.

00:51:58.236 --> 00:51:59.860
I think that athletes
with disabilities

00:51:59.860 --> 00:52:02.330
are almost following
a path where we've

00:52:02.330 --> 00:52:04.854
seen women athletes come from.

00:52:04.854 --> 00:52:06.520
No matter how it's
presented or couched,

00:52:06.520 --> 00:52:08.395
discrimination towards
students of disability

00:52:08.395 --> 00:52:09.850
is still discrimination.

00:52:09.850 --> 00:52:12.650
And it's very similar to issues
surrounding race, gender,

00:52:12.650 --> 00:52:14.020
sexual orientation.

00:52:14.020 --> 00:52:17.410
So the process
that women athletes

00:52:17.410 --> 00:52:20.979
had to go through during Title
IX to get access to sport,

00:52:20.979 --> 00:52:23.020
our student athletes are
going through right now.

00:52:23.020 --> 00:52:28.874
It's a very relevant time
for our student athletes.

00:52:28.874 --> 00:52:30.790
We are often viewed as
not equal to our peers.

00:52:30.790 --> 00:52:33.057
I see this every
single day on campus

00:52:33.057 --> 00:52:35.140
at the University of
Illinois, and we are actually

00:52:35.140 --> 00:52:37.910
seeing someone who is a
leader in this aspect,

00:52:37.910 --> 00:52:41.500
but on a day to day basis,
I see the inequality

00:52:41.500 --> 00:52:44.350
of what our student
athletes have to go through.

00:52:44.350 --> 00:52:48.520
Small example, access to the
student athlete dining hall.

00:52:48.520 --> 00:52:50.777
Something that
seems pretty simple.

00:52:50.777 --> 00:52:52.360
Where student athletes
can go in, they

00:52:52.360 --> 00:52:54.526
can grab food on their way
to class, after practice,

00:52:54.526 --> 00:52:56.440
ability to recover,
our student athletes

00:52:56.440 --> 00:52:58.900
don't have access
to that option.

00:52:58.900 --> 00:53:02.500
They have to fend for meals
however they can fend for meals

00:53:02.500 --> 00:53:04.210
to properly recover.

00:53:04.210 --> 00:53:06.490
Small example, but
has a huge impact

00:53:06.490 --> 00:53:10.590
across the board in what our
student athletes experience.

00:53:13.907 --> 00:53:15.240
I think oldness and perceptions.

00:53:15.240 --> 00:53:15.739
I think

00:53:15.739 --> 00:53:18.984
That is probably the
single biggest barrier

00:53:18.984 --> 00:53:20.650
to students with
disabilities right now.

00:53:20.650 --> 00:53:23.024
Again, it goes back to that
similarity of women in sport.

00:53:23.024 --> 00:53:25.140
Like what were the old
myths and stereotypes

00:53:25.140 --> 00:53:28.270
that women had to deal with as
we spoke about earlier with.

00:53:28.270 --> 00:53:30.029
It's not good, physically.

00:53:30.029 --> 00:53:32.070
You're going to stop having
your menstrual cycle.

00:53:32.070 --> 00:53:33.930
All of those things
that are there

00:53:33.930 --> 00:53:36.540
based on myths and
stereotypes, you

00:53:36.540 --> 00:53:39.760
encounter those with our student
athletes with disabilities.

00:53:39.760 --> 00:53:42.932
So we see able-bodied
sport is the norm.

00:53:42.932 --> 00:53:45.390
There is a diminished value of
sport and leisure activities

00:53:45.390 --> 00:53:47.010
for people with disabilities.

00:53:47.010 --> 00:53:49.500
There's lack of education and
expertise on what disability

00:53:49.500 --> 00:53:51.720
sport is and who can play.

00:53:51.720 --> 00:53:53.535
And there's a wide
range of individuals

00:53:53.535 --> 00:53:57.450
of who can play disability
sport, and that kind of leads

00:53:57.450 --> 00:54:01.362
into that next piece,
which is classification.

00:54:01.362 --> 00:54:02.820
I'll come back to
that in a second.

00:54:02.820 --> 00:54:05.490
So just the role
of gender and how

00:54:05.490 --> 00:54:08.160
it combines with disability.

00:54:08.160 --> 00:54:09.930
When we go back
and we look at what

00:54:09.930 --> 00:54:14.340
those myths and stereotypes
are for gender, again--

00:54:14.340 --> 00:54:16.410
sorry, with disability--
they bleed into gender.

00:54:16.410 --> 00:54:19.090
So how does society attach
meaning to disability?

00:54:19.090 --> 00:54:21.336
When we have an
image in our minds

00:54:21.336 --> 00:54:22.710
of what someone
with a disability

00:54:22.710 --> 00:54:24.530
looks like, what
they're able to do,

00:54:24.530 --> 00:54:25.740
we have pretty low standards.

00:54:25.740 --> 00:54:27.698
Or historically we've
had pretty low standards,

00:54:27.698 --> 00:54:28.920
low expectations.

00:54:28.920 --> 00:54:30.960
We don't expect
them to be physical.

00:54:30.960 --> 00:54:34.440
We don't expect them to
expect physical activity.

00:54:34.440 --> 00:54:37.350
We don't expect them to be able
to achieve on a high level.

00:54:37.350 --> 00:54:40.080
We hold them to lower standards.

00:54:40.080 --> 00:54:44.790
A lot of this evolves out of
the medical model of disability.

00:54:44.790 --> 00:54:47.310
And I think in order to take
that next step with disability

00:54:47.310 --> 00:54:49.350
sport, it's evolving into
more of a social model

00:54:49.350 --> 00:54:52.232
with disability, and so
it's surrounded with pity.

00:54:52.232 --> 00:54:53.940
You look at that person
with a disability

00:54:53.940 --> 00:54:56.398
and you kind of feel sorry for
them that they can't do this

00:54:56.398 --> 00:54:57.810
or can't do that.

00:54:57.810 --> 00:55:01.237
And so what we try to do with
disability sport, and now

00:55:01.237 --> 00:55:02.820
adding in gender
into it, we're trying

00:55:02.820 --> 00:55:04.830
to flip that and attach
a different meaning

00:55:04.830 --> 00:55:06.142
to disability.

00:55:06.142 --> 00:55:08.100
So looking at the social
construction of sport,

00:55:08.100 --> 00:55:09.960
that is also a
critical factor that

00:55:09.960 --> 00:55:12.450
impacts perceptions related
to the participation of women

00:55:12.450 --> 00:55:14.197
with physical
disabilities in sport.

00:55:14.197 --> 00:55:15.780
Because now you have
these conceptions

00:55:15.780 --> 00:55:18.420
of what individuals with
disability looks like,

00:55:18.420 --> 00:55:21.090
what they're capable are,
now you add gender onto it

00:55:21.090 --> 00:55:23.190
and you get that
double whammy effect.

00:55:23.190 --> 00:55:24.414
And so someone who--

00:55:24.414 --> 00:55:25.830
an individual with
a disability is

00:55:25.830 --> 00:55:30.420
supposed to be frail, fragile,
weak, low expectations,

00:55:30.420 --> 00:55:31.650
not being physical.

00:55:31.650 --> 00:55:33.840
You confound that
now with a female who

00:55:33.840 --> 00:55:37.440
is supposed to be weak, sit on
the sidelines, clap politely,

00:55:37.440 --> 00:55:39.330
and you put those
two together, and you

00:55:39.330 --> 00:55:42.840
create this rub between
what our expectations are,

00:55:42.840 --> 00:55:46.200
and what reality can be, and
what we have the opportunity

00:55:46.200 --> 00:55:47.080
to do.

00:55:47.080 --> 00:55:50.620
So it leads to those
conflicting expectations.

00:55:50.620 --> 00:55:52.980
We do have negative
perceptions and stereotypes.

00:55:52.980 --> 00:55:55.110
I can't tell you how
many times that I've

00:55:55.110 --> 00:55:56.839
heard it's so great
that you guys get

00:55:56.839 --> 00:55:58.380
to get out and play
sport, and that's

00:55:58.380 --> 00:55:59.910
just on the disability level.

00:55:59.910 --> 00:56:05.710
Or as a female athlete, times
where my team was really good,

00:56:05.710 --> 00:56:07.710
and we had to play against
men's teams, and some

00:56:07.710 --> 00:56:11.300
of the derogatory terms that you
heard, telling you to get off

00:56:11.300 --> 00:56:13.800
the court, telling you you're
not welcome against this team,

00:56:13.800 --> 00:56:15.550
telling you they're
going to come back out

00:56:15.550 --> 00:56:17.070
and beat up one
of your teammates.

00:56:17.070 --> 00:56:19.890
Those were things that were just
realities as we moved forward

00:56:19.890 --> 00:56:21.660
through this process.

00:56:21.660 --> 00:56:25.020
Just to give a couple
of examples touching

00:56:25.020 --> 00:56:26.265
on the Paralympic games.

00:56:26.265 --> 00:56:29.460
So we had about
38% participation,

00:56:29.460 --> 00:56:31.590
43% of medal events,
which was almost

00:56:31.590 --> 00:56:32.950
a 10% increase from London.

00:56:32.950 --> 00:56:34.050
So that's positive.

00:56:34.050 --> 00:56:35.430
That piece is growing.

00:56:35.430 --> 00:56:38.161
So that's kind of the
role that gender plays.

00:56:38.161 --> 00:56:39.660
What I'm going to
do really quickly,

00:56:39.660 --> 00:56:41.776
because I'm running
out of time, is

00:56:41.776 --> 00:56:44.400
run through a real world example
of what's happening right now.

00:56:44.400 --> 00:56:46.170
There's been a little bit of
slowed progress with this,

00:56:46.170 --> 00:56:47.795
but those of you guys
on the east coast

00:56:47.795 --> 00:56:52.230
know about the ECAC, a really
awesome athletic conference.

00:56:52.230 --> 00:56:55.200
What they have done is they've
adopted an inclusive sport

00:56:55.200 --> 00:56:58.820
model a couple of
years ago, and it's

00:56:58.820 --> 00:57:00.570
based on principles
of inclusion depending

00:57:00.570 --> 00:57:03.120
on a person's specific
disability, and their ability

00:57:03.120 --> 00:57:04.570
to compete at a varsity level.

00:57:04.570 --> 00:57:06.420
Otherwise qualified, right? ?

00:57:06.420 --> 00:57:08.880
So as we kind of go through
of what inclusive sport

00:57:08.880 --> 00:57:11.700
looks like, and this will be
a really quick run through,

00:57:11.700 --> 00:57:13.620
the first couple of principals--

00:57:13.620 --> 00:57:17.010
student athletes can
participate on existing teams

00:57:17.010 --> 00:57:20.040
with either no accommodations
or some small accommodations

00:57:20.040 --> 00:57:21.870
that don't effect the sport.

00:57:21.870 --> 00:57:22.870
So if we look at--

00:57:22.870 --> 00:57:23.790
that's Marla Runyan.

00:57:23.790 --> 00:57:26.760
She's the first runner
there, blind athlete,

00:57:26.760 --> 00:57:28.260
able to run without a guide.

00:57:28.260 --> 00:57:30.242
Doesn't significantly
impact the sport.

00:57:30.242 --> 00:57:32.200
We have Anthony Robles
here, who is a wrestler.

00:57:32.200 --> 00:57:35.140
Won a division one national
title at Arizona State.

00:57:35.140 --> 00:57:37.590
A swimmer here, competing
for her university.

00:57:37.590 --> 00:57:40.930
So that does not
significantly alter sport.

00:57:40.930 --> 00:57:42.960
You're not changing the sport.

00:57:42.960 --> 00:57:45.150
Third principle,
inclusion of athletes

00:57:45.150 --> 00:57:47.550
with a disability through the
addition of adapted events.

00:57:47.550 --> 00:57:50.100
This is when you see track
and field athletes who compete

00:57:50.100 --> 00:57:51.280
in our wheelchair divisions.

00:57:51.280 --> 00:57:53.970
That's Tatiana McFadden.

00:57:53.970 --> 00:57:56.430
The addition of
events with a guide

00:57:56.430 --> 00:57:59.430
runner for amputees that
are separate events,

00:57:59.430 --> 00:58:03.750
but you're still winning points,
so to say, at your events.

00:58:03.750 --> 00:58:07.332
Swimming, there's rowing,
wheelchair tennis.

00:58:07.332 --> 00:58:08.790
And then lastly,
it's the inclusion

00:58:08.790 --> 00:58:10.890
of athletes with a disability
through the creation

00:58:10.890 --> 00:58:12.032
of adapted team sports.

00:58:12.032 --> 00:58:14.240
And this is kind of what I
was talking about earlier.

00:58:14.240 --> 00:58:15.830
This is where the
donut hole exists.

00:58:15.830 --> 00:58:18.140
This is where we don't do a
really great job right now

00:58:18.140 --> 00:58:20.690
at the Scholastic level
of inclusion of athletes

00:58:20.690 --> 00:58:21.969
with disabilities.

00:58:21.969 --> 00:58:23.510
And so this is
wheelchair basketball.

00:58:23.510 --> 00:58:25.430
It's kind of your
traditional team sports.

00:58:25.430 --> 00:58:28.940
Sled hockey, sitting
volleyball, and goalball.

00:58:28.940 --> 00:58:32.120
So that's a really
quick and dirty version

00:58:32.120 --> 00:58:35.180
of where we are with
disability sport.

00:58:35.180 --> 00:58:36.500
Where we've come from.

00:58:36.500 --> 00:58:38.710
How it's been seen as a
privilege for individuals

00:58:38.710 --> 00:58:41.390
with disabilities to be able
to participate in sport.

00:58:41.390 --> 00:58:44.590
How that then
compounds with gender

00:58:44.590 --> 00:58:47.210
and makes it even more
difficult to access with

00:58:47.210 --> 00:58:50.000
added layers of discrimination
for women with disabilities.

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:52.380
And then where we can
be, and the future,

00:58:52.380 --> 00:58:55.010
and where we can go
with disability sport

00:58:55.010 --> 00:58:56.900
if we just think
outside of that model

00:58:56.900 --> 00:58:59.218
that we have right
now for sport.

00:58:59.218 --> 00:59:01.154
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:08.910 --> 00:59:11.560
- Well, I would like
to commend my panelists

00:59:11.560 --> 00:59:16.870
for coming in on time or
under time, and also giving us

00:59:16.870 --> 00:59:19.900
so much to think about
just to start our day,

00:59:19.900 --> 00:59:21.370
and that's really
what we had hoped

00:59:21.370 --> 00:59:23.900
for when we're planning this.

00:59:23.900 --> 00:59:26.770
I think what I'd like
to do is allow them

00:59:26.770 --> 00:59:33.270
to step back and talk about
some big issues and some

00:59:33.270 --> 00:59:35.920
of the themes that
have come through.

00:59:35.920 --> 00:59:39.100
And I think the one
that really sticks out

00:59:39.100 --> 00:59:44.230
for me is this idea of
sports as a birthright

00:59:44.230 --> 00:59:48.850
that all humans
enjoy and then also

00:59:48.850 --> 00:59:51.700
what are the
challenges women face

00:59:51.700 --> 00:59:53.110
in claiming that birthright?

00:59:53.110 --> 00:59:55.240
But I think, Anita, for
you especially, that's

00:59:55.240 --> 00:59:57.786
your philosophy of sports.

00:59:57.786 --> 01:00:00.984
- Yeah, for a long
time I believed that.

01:00:00.984 --> 01:00:03.400
Maybe growing up with three
brothers and not understanding

01:00:03.400 --> 01:00:06.280
why I couldn't get onto
the basketball court,

01:00:06.280 --> 01:00:08.950
and I couldn't, I couldn't,
couldn't, couldn't.

01:00:08.950 --> 01:00:13.510
It didn't make sense to me why
I did not have this access.

01:00:13.510 --> 01:00:15.100
My parents were well evolved.

01:00:15.100 --> 01:00:18.790
I could cut the grass and my
brothers could wash the dishes,

01:00:18.790 --> 01:00:22.960
but there was this whole
area that disallowed me.

01:00:22.960 --> 01:00:26.560
And it did not seem
fair and it wasn't fair

01:00:26.560 --> 01:00:31.420
because all humans have this
desire to take part in sport.

01:00:31.420 --> 01:00:34.180
It's the one thing
that we do as a species

01:00:34.180 --> 01:00:36.910
that no other species does.

01:00:36.910 --> 01:00:39.850
If you've heard me speak before
I reference the fact that

01:00:39.850 --> 01:00:42.830
what other species sets up
hurdles and races across them

01:00:42.830 --> 01:00:45.250
to see who gets across
the finish line first?

01:00:45.250 --> 01:00:47.920
I referenced that I've seen
an ant climb onto a twig

01:00:47.920 --> 01:00:49.270
to get across a puddle of water.

01:00:49.270 --> 01:00:51.130
I've never seen them
line up those twigs

01:00:51.130 --> 01:00:52.990
to get across a puddle of water.

01:00:52.990 --> 01:00:55.480
It's something that
we enjoy doing.

01:00:55.480 --> 01:00:56.860
We enjoy talking about it.

01:00:56.860 --> 01:00:58.600
We enjoy taking part in sport.

01:00:58.600 --> 01:01:01.060
We enjoy the history of it.

01:01:01.060 --> 01:01:03.130
It brings us together
as communities.

01:01:03.130 --> 01:01:06.970
It helps us enjoy
people's success.

01:01:06.970 --> 01:01:09.940
It helps us get into that
zone of excellence, which

01:01:09.940 --> 01:01:11.680
I think we need to study more.

01:01:11.680 --> 01:01:14.260
But it's something
that we do as humans

01:01:14.260 --> 01:01:15.880
and it's not just some humans.

01:01:15.880 --> 01:01:18.680
It's not just one
half of humanity.

01:01:18.680 --> 01:01:22.140
It's all of humans.

01:01:22.140 --> 01:01:24.570
- I completely agree and
I, again, I look at this

01:01:24.570 --> 01:01:26.400
through the lens of disability.

01:01:26.400 --> 01:01:29.670
And it's something,
like I mentioned,

01:01:29.670 --> 01:01:33.120
where it's seen as
individuals with disabilities,

01:01:33.120 --> 01:01:35.040
that they don't have
the desire to compete.

01:01:35.040 --> 01:01:39.570
They don't have the desire
to challenge themselves

01:01:39.570 --> 01:01:42.880
at that high level, and
that's just completely untrue.

01:01:42.880 --> 01:01:45.090
I think if you look
across the board,

01:01:45.090 --> 01:01:48.690
internationally, there are
no barriers in place over

01:01:48.690 --> 01:01:50.790
and over again that
show those individuals

01:01:50.790 --> 01:01:52.050
that it is a privilege.

01:01:54.750 --> 01:01:56.640
It addresses that
larger question

01:01:56.640 --> 01:01:58.260
of what bodies
are able, and what

01:01:58.260 --> 01:02:01.350
bodies do we see as able,
and from a gender perspective

01:02:01.350 --> 01:02:03.000
and from a disability
perspective.

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:06.760
And what bodies have the right
to be able to participate.

01:02:06.760 --> 01:02:10.510
So I completely agree with that.

01:02:10.510 --> 01:02:14.640
And it's important that
we, as much as we can,

01:02:14.640 --> 01:02:16.790
remove those systemic barriers.

01:02:16.790 --> 01:02:20.880
That's what creates
sport as a privilege,

01:02:20.880 --> 01:02:22.880
is that there's those
systemic barriers in place

01:02:22.880 --> 01:02:25.421
of saying who can play and who
can get to that starting line.

01:02:25.421 --> 01:02:27.540
And so it's kind of
on us and everybody

01:02:27.540 --> 01:02:30.570
here to begin to remove
those and re-conceptualize,

01:02:30.570 --> 01:02:33.960
especially-- again, I come from
the disability sport angle.

01:02:33.960 --> 01:02:36.080
Re-conceptualize
what that looks like.

01:02:36.080 --> 01:02:39.960
Re-conceptualize what sport
looks like, and what bodies

01:02:39.960 --> 01:02:44.900
that can compete look like,
and how it's their right.

01:02:44.900 --> 01:02:48.000
- I think we're speaking
to the choir in terms

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:51.680
of our birthright.

01:02:51.680 --> 01:02:55.610
Seriously, no child should ever
be told that you cannot pursue

01:02:55.610 --> 01:02:56.260
your dreams.

01:02:56.260 --> 01:02:59.480
I don't care whether it's sport,
or being an engineer, or a fire

01:02:59.480 --> 01:03:01.100
person, or any of it.

01:03:01.100 --> 01:03:02.960
I think we're all in that mode.

01:03:02.960 --> 01:03:05.810
But if the right
has been denied,

01:03:05.810 --> 01:03:09.830
then I think we have
to jump into can

01:03:09.830 --> 01:03:15.230
we change the legal system
to make sure it's a right?

01:03:15.230 --> 01:03:16.890
And that's what was
done with Title IX.

01:03:16.890 --> 01:03:18.890
I thought it was very
interesting in Stephanie's

01:03:18.890 --> 01:03:22.010
presentation, you can
see the Dear Colleague

01:03:22.010 --> 01:03:27.080
letter on disability did
not come out until 2014.

01:03:27.080 --> 01:03:30.050
And that's the equivalent
of the regulation

01:03:30.050 --> 01:03:33.740
that got done before Title
IX was even in place.

01:03:33.740 --> 01:03:37.730
And I could kick myself having
been with the Women's Sports

01:03:37.730 --> 01:03:42.350
Foundation in not
embracing the need,

01:03:42.350 --> 01:03:44.270
in the case of
disabled sport, to go

01:03:44.270 --> 01:03:49.040
after those same regulations
under disability.

01:03:49.040 --> 01:03:51.860
No excuse.

01:03:51.860 --> 01:03:55.632
Fortunately, Terri Lakowski
from the foundation

01:03:55.632 --> 01:03:57.590
was very helpful in that
Dear Colleague letter.

01:03:57.590 --> 01:04:01.800
But if McFadden never called
the Women's Sports Foundation,

01:04:01.800 --> 01:04:03.290
Terri wouldn't have been there.

01:04:03.290 --> 01:04:06.470
That Dear Colleague letter
wouldn't have been there.

