Or does anybody in
the audience who's

01:04:40.060 --> 01:04:43.060
a lawyer want to come in on--

01:04:43.060 --> 01:04:45.520
- My answer would be possibly.

01:04:45.520 --> 01:04:49.450
- Because that's what
happened in Canada.

01:04:49.450 --> 01:04:52.030
When our American
women challenged

01:04:52.030 --> 01:04:55.660
the use of artificial
turf for World Cup--

01:04:55.660 --> 01:04:56.820
- Soccer, football.

01:04:56.820 --> 01:05:03.610
- In Canada, they
don't have a right

01:05:03.610 --> 01:05:06.640
to pursue civil rights
actions in the courts.

01:05:06.640 --> 01:05:10.689
It's a Civil Rights Commission
that's a weak sister.

01:05:10.689 --> 01:05:12.480
So that would have been
the place to do it,

01:05:12.480 --> 01:05:13.420
you now what I mean?

01:05:13.420 --> 01:05:15.190
- But they have a
different system

01:05:15.190 --> 01:05:17.270
because sports is a
part of the government,

01:05:17.270 --> 01:05:19.540
unlike the system in
the United States.

01:05:19.540 --> 01:05:23.200
So they have other
avenues to take action.

01:05:23.200 --> 01:05:25.230
- It's an interesting place.

01:05:25.230 --> 01:05:27.560
- We still haven't
signed [INAUDIBLE] yet.

01:05:27.560 --> 01:05:29.260
- Yeah.

01:05:29.260 --> 01:05:32.680
- I'm a historian, and I at one
point had looked to see whether

01:05:32.680 --> 01:05:35.920
there was anything equivalent
to Title IX, globally,

01:05:35.920 --> 01:05:38.020
and there wasn't.

01:05:38.020 --> 01:05:41.500
There does seem to be, through
the various United Nations

01:05:41.500 --> 01:05:45.550
commissions on women in
International Women's Year,

01:05:45.550 --> 01:05:48.760
the topic began to
get on the agenda.

01:05:48.760 --> 01:05:52.810
And it seems that the break out
decade for the United States

01:05:52.810 --> 01:05:54.130
was the 70s.

01:05:54.130 --> 01:05:56.470
I think, globally,
the breakout decade

01:05:56.470 --> 01:05:58.930
was the 90s, when
things really started

01:05:58.930 --> 01:06:01.330
to pop in terms of gender.

01:06:01.330 --> 01:06:04.210
And I think that the UN
had a lot to do with that.

01:06:04.210 --> 01:06:06.260
But I think this
raises another question

01:06:06.260 --> 01:06:09.280
I wanted us to weigh in on
because it's relevant really

01:06:09.280 --> 01:06:11.560
to what we're doing
the rest of the day.

01:06:11.560 --> 01:06:14.830
The United States
sports system is not

01:06:14.830 --> 01:06:19.270
the way sport is organized
in the rest of the world.

01:06:19.270 --> 01:06:23.999
And I know we have a
very literate audience,

01:06:23.999 --> 01:06:25.540
but I thought we
should maybe explore

01:06:25.540 --> 01:06:28.870
some of the ways in which
the situation we kind of take

01:06:28.870 --> 01:06:34.030
for granted is not necessarily
how sport is organized starting

01:06:34.030 --> 01:06:37.390
with state support for sports.

01:06:37.390 --> 01:06:40.100
So I don't know which of you--

01:06:40.100 --> 01:06:42.241
- Let me just say this
one piece of the puzzle

01:06:42.241 --> 01:06:43.990
and I think that's a
very important point.

01:06:43.990 --> 01:06:46.570
Because we're one of the
few countries in the world

01:06:46.570 --> 01:06:49.530
by to embed sport within
educational systems,

01:06:49.530 --> 01:06:52.990
and because
education is a right,

01:06:52.990 --> 01:06:55.900
our legal system
followed that thinking.

01:06:55.900 --> 01:07:00.750
And what Congress really did
was as part of the Education

01:07:00.750 --> 01:07:04.180
Amendments Act, as a condition
of higher education funding,

01:07:04.180 --> 01:07:10.570
it attached this right
to education to sport.

01:07:10.570 --> 01:07:12.430
We're the only place
in the world, I think,

01:07:12.430 --> 01:07:15.280
that does that because
everything else is

01:07:15.280 --> 01:07:18.435
clubs outside of the
educational system.

01:07:18.435 --> 01:07:20.350
- Well, in Europe,
there's a have a right

01:07:20.350 --> 01:07:24.010
to work part to it.

01:07:24.010 --> 01:07:27.670
Sports are protected, but only
once you get to the point where

01:07:27.670 --> 01:07:29.620
it your advocation--

01:07:29.620 --> 01:07:32.200
your vocation, not advocation.

01:07:32.200 --> 01:07:34.120
- Yeah, absolutely.

01:07:34.120 --> 01:07:36.730
- I think for us, for
athletes of disabilities,

01:07:36.730 --> 01:07:43.480
I think our process is directly
tied to the education process.

01:07:43.480 --> 01:07:45.760
Physical activity is a part
of the education process

01:07:45.760 --> 01:07:49.060
of children with disabilities
that has been largely ignored.

01:07:49.060 --> 01:07:50.920
And I can speak from
personal experience

01:07:50.920 --> 01:07:53.710
on that as far as physical
education opportunities

01:07:53.710 --> 01:07:55.990
within school and
then opportunities

01:07:55.990 --> 01:07:59.950
outside of school for
recreational opportunities.

01:07:59.950 --> 01:08:01.960
And so that's been
the big push, is

01:08:01.960 --> 01:08:05.130
the tie to education for
individuals with disabilities.

01:08:05.130 --> 01:08:08.530
They're missing this huge piece
of their right to be educated.

01:08:08.530 --> 01:08:10.840
And then the other
side of that too

01:08:10.840 --> 01:08:15.760
is we see the education process
of the larger population

01:08:15.760 --> 01:08:17.170
or public of that school.

01:08:17.170 --> 01:08:19.422
Because we have such
that ingrained picture

01:08:19.422 --> 01:08:21.880
of what an individual with a
disability looks like and what

01:08:21.880 --> 01:08:22.960
they can do.

01:08:22.960 --> 01:08:25.660
And so when you take that
individual for someone

01:08:25.660 --> 01:08:29.036
who sits on the sidelines
at PE, they keep score.

01:08:29.036 --> 01:08:30.910
They're the goalie that
just sits in the goal

01:08:30.910 --> 01:08:32.140
and they don't do anything.

01:08:32.140 --> 01:08:34.473
When you take them and you
move them from that position,

01:08:34.473 --> 01:08:37.090
and you put them into a
position where they're active,

01:08:37.090 --> 01:08:40.090
and they're actively giving
to that social environment,

01:08:40.090 --> 01:08:41.620
it completely
changes the paradigm

01:08:41.620 --> 01:08:43.859
and the lens through
which you see that person.

01:08:43.859 --> 01:08:46.750
So it educates the rest of
the class, or the school,

01:08:46.750 --> 01:08:48.340
or whatever it might be.

01:08:48.340 --> 01:08:50.620
And so it's tied to
the educational process

01:08:50.620 --> 01:08:53.109
in two really big
ways, which makes it--

01:08:53.109 --> 01:08:56.600
that's that educational
right of everyone.

01:08:56.600 --> 01:08:58.600
- I think I have one more
question for the panel

01:08:58.600 --> 01:09:00.229
before I open it up.

01:09:00.229 --> 01:09:01.930
It really came to
me this morning

01:09:01.930 --> 01:09:07.180
and I was thinking that
here I have three women who

01:09:07.180 --> 01:09:12.010
have been able, or are in the
process, of making a career out

01:09:12.010 --> 01:09:14.470
of being in the world of sports.

01:09:14.470 --> 01:09:17.350
And I think that is
something we should mark

01:09:17.350 --> 01:09:19.510
and it didn't used to happen.

01:09:19.510 --> 01:09:21.490
But I wondered,
since you all have

01:09:21.490 --> 01:09:23.890
been able to really
do that, if you

01:09:23.890 --> 01:09:28.630
had had any advice for people
as they're contemplating

01:09:28.630 --> 01:09:30.370
a career in this area.

01:09:30.370 --> 01:09:31.840
I mean, we've
certainly given them

01:09:31.840 --> 01:09:35.240
plenty of reasons to realize
why it needs to be done,

01:09:35.240 --> 01:09:38.328
but if there is anything
you wanted to pass along.

01:09:41.479 --> 01:09:45.051
- Well, you know [INAUDIBLE].

01:09:45.051 --> 01:09:48.050
I think the barriers
to women in sport right

01:09:48.050 --> 01:09:51.439
now are the male
dominance of men.

01:09:51.439 --> 01:09:55.520
This whole issue of
homologous reproduction

01:09:55.520 --> 01:09:58.400
where the current
white male power

01:09:58.400 --> 01:10:02.790
structure is in the process
of reproducing itself,

01:10:02.790 --> 01:10:05.600
not necessarily
intentionally, but we

01:10:05.600 --> 01:10:07.280
hire people who look like us.

01:10:07.280 --> 01:10:10.820
We hire people who
are comfortable

01:10:10.820 --> 01:10:13.175
and this is a systems problem.

01:10:13.175 --> 01:10:17.390
We have to have schools and
support organizations that

01:10:17.390 --> 01:10:20.300
follow systems that
prevent discrimination

01:10:20.300 --> 01:10:23.780
in terms of hiring, and
that means search committees

01:10:23.780 --> 01:10:25.250
that are a minority dominated.

01:10:25.250 --> 01:10:28.790
That means not one
of your finalists

01:10:28.790 --> 01:10:32.690
being a minority person,
it means at least 30%.

01:10:32.690 --> 01:10:36.080
Research shows at least
30% of that finalist pool

01:10:36.080 --> 01:10:41.120
has to be an under-represented
minority in order

01:10:41.120 --> 01:10:43.220
for this change to take place.

01:10:43.220 --> 01:10:46.520
We've got to hit all those
spots and we have not

01:10:46.520 --> 01:10:50.240
done that in terms of this
organizational system that

01:10:50.240 --> 01:10:51.200
has to be put in place.

01:10:54.170 --> 01:10:57.350
- One thing I would say
is I didn't listen to--

01:11:00.860 --> 01:11:02.422
I had a couple of opportunities.

01:11:02.422 --> 01:11:04.880
So I've been fortunate to coach
at the international level,

01:11:04.880 --> 01:11:07.340
both at the junior and
senior national team level.

01:11:07.340 --> 01:11:11.160
And at the Paralympic games
last year, I was the--

01:11:11.160 --> 01:11:13.160
for wheelchair basketball,
I was the only female

01:11:13.160 --> 01:11:15.535
with a disability that was
the head coach of a wheelchair

01:11:15.535 --> 01:11:21.450
basketball team, and that's
just unacceptable in our sport.

01:11:21.450 --> 01:11:25.580
And the path to get
there was challenging.

01:11:25.580 --> 01:11:27.710
My first international
coaching job

01:11:27.710 --> 01:11:32.840
I actually gotten a roundabout
way with a male being

01:11:32.840 --> 01:11:36.410
selected to do the job who was
significantly under qualified.

01:11:36.410 --> 01:11:37.520
I was his assistant coach.

01:11:37.520 --> 01:11:38.210
He quit.

01:11:38.210 --> 01:11:40.250
Now he's moved up to the
head coaching position.

01:11:40.250 --> 01:11:42.584
And when I was starting
to think that coaching

01:11:42.584 --> 01:11:44.000
the senior national
team was going

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:47.150
to be where I wanted
my career to go,

01:11:47.150 --> 01:11:49.670
our high performance
director at the time

01:11:49.670 --> 01:11:51.950
told me that I needed
take an opportunity

01:11:51.950 --> 01:11:56.780
to be an assistant coach with
our men's junior national team

01:11:56.780 --> 01:11:57.680
first.

01:11:57.680 --> 01:11:59.990
And I was like, nah,
that doesn't sound right,

01:11:59.990 --> 01:12:01.490
and that's not
what I want to do.

01:12:01.490 --> 01:12:03.115
I want to make sure
that I'm continuing

01:12:03.115 --> 01:12:06.170
on this path with coaching
women and empowering women,

01:12:06.170 --> 01:12:08.780
and I don't need
to take that step

01:12:08.780 --> 01:12:13.120
over in what he saw was a
step up, this lateral step,

01:12:13.120 --> 01:12:15.260
to make myself look better.

01:12:15.260 --> 01:12:16.010
There's no way.

01:12:16.010 --> 01:12:20.630
And so I think for me it
was I had the strength

01:12:20.630 --> 01:12:24.154
to stick to my guns in that way,
and know the path that I wanted

01:12:24.154 --> 01:12:25.820
to be on, and who I
wanted to influence,

01:12:25.820 --> 01:12:27.230
and where I wanted to go.

01:12:27.230 --> 01:12:29.540
Fortunately, I was
able to overcome that,

01:12:29.540 --> 01:12:31.970
but what always sticks in
my mind in my conversation

01:12:31.970 --> 01:12:33.860
with him is he told
me-- he's like you know,

01:12:33.860 --> 01:12:36.110
you came into that junior
national team coaching job

01:12:36.110 --> 01:12:37.460
through the back door.

01:12:37.460 --> 01:12:39.409
And I'm like, you have
got to be kidding me.

01:12:39.409 --> 01:12:40.700
You have to be kidding me like.

01:12:40.700 --> 01:12:42.440
I outright earned that job.

01:12:42.440 --> 01:12:44.360
And so that always
sticks with me

01:12:44.360 --> 01:12:49.190
in that process of
just really critically

01:12:49.190 --> 01:12:51.846
thinking about the opportunity
that's in front of you

01:12:51.846 --> 01:12:53.720
and knowing if that's
really going to get you

01:12:53.720 --> 01:12:54.860
where you want to be.

01:12:54.860 --> 01:12:56.920
And if what this person
who is a-- and he

01:12:56.920 --> 01:12:59.810
was a white, able-bodied
male, what he was telling me

01:12:59.810 --> 01:13:02.409
I needed to do in
order to achieve

01:13:02.409 --> 01:13:03.450
what I wanted to achieve.

01:13:03.450 --> 01:13:04.670
And so that's something
that's always stuck with me,

01:13:04.670 --> 01:13:06.590
and I try to tell
that to anybody

01:13:06.590 --> 01:13:08.360
that I talk to, female
with a disability,

01:13:08.360 --> 01:13:09.651
without a disability, whatever.

01:13:09.651 --> 01:13:12.410
Is just that you kind of have
to know where you're going

01:13:12.410 --> 01:13:16.820
and have an idea of it, and know
that what someone is telling

01:13:16.820 --> 01:13:18.950
you that's a move up,
if it's not a move up,

01:13:18.950 --> 01:13:23.349
if it doesn't vibe with
what your passion is,

01:13:23.349 --> 01:13:24.390
and where you want to go.

01:13:24.390 --> 01:13:27.470
So that would be the
advice that I have.

01:13:27.470 --> 01:13:29.150
- I want to agree
with Stephanie.

01:13:29.150 --> 01:13:31.550
Naivety is a great thing.

01:13:31.550 --> 01:13:33.080
- Oh, I was super naive.

01:13:33.080 --> 01:13:34.819
I was young and super naive.

01:13:34.819 --> 01:13:36.860
- So was I when I went to
the University of Texas

01:13:36.860 --> 01:13:39.872
as the first Director
of Women's Athletics.

01:13:39.872 --> 01:13:42.080
I really thought Texas wanted
a National Championship

01:13:42.080 --> 01:13:45.230
Program and that's what
I was supposed to do.

01:13:45.230 --> 01:13:50.090
And so I was a 29-year-old naive
person, but I acted that way,

01:13:50.090 --> 01:13:52.400
and I didn't know any
better, which is good.

01:13:52.400 --> 01:13:55.040
And I think the
other thing is do not

01:13:55.040 --> 01:13:59.330
go through this mental process
of I have to be qualified.

01:13:59.330 --> 01:14:02.930
No male ever did that for a job.

01:14:02.930 --> 01:14:03.860
Ever.

01:14:03.860 --> 01:14:05.630
[APPLAUSE]

01:14:07.250 --> 01:14:11.330
You are probably more educated
than your male counterpart

01:14:11.330 --> 01:14:14.060
and there's no job
that you can't learn

01:14:14.060 --> 01:14:17.690
and so you might as well just
go after what it is you want.

01:14:17.690 --> 01:14:21.230
You're going to be better
than 90% of the population.

01:14:21.230 --> 01:14:23.780
- I think one more thing to
add-- sorry, really quickly--

01:14:23.780 --> 01:14:25.340
that I think is
really important,

01:14:25.340 --> 01:14:28.167
and something I had to
learn through my naivety,

01:14:28.167 --> 01:14:29.750
was that it's really
important to have

01:14:29.750 --> 01:14:32.120
a strong team around you.

01:14:32.120 --> 01:14:35.570
And I have been really fortunate
to have a lot of great mentors

01:14:35.570 --> 01:14:36.780
throughout my career.

01:14:36.780 --> 01:14:38.821
And one of the things I
was really hesitant to do

01:14:38.821 --> 01:14:43.130
was reach out, and reach out to
people for advice and support.

01:14:43.130 --> 01:14:46.160
I thought that was kind
of a brown nosing thing

01:14:46.160 --> 01:14:47.990
or I just had a really
negative conception

01:14:47.990 --> 01:14:50.480
of what that whole
networking piece looked like.

01:14:50.480 --> 01:14:53.990
But it's so important that
you find people, and surround

01:14:53.990 --> 01:14:56.760
yourself with people who
have been on that path,

01:14:56.760 --> 01:14:58.760
and who can help guide
you through that journey.

01:14:58.760 --> 01:15:01.550
I wouldn't be
anywhere near where

01:15:01.550 --> 01:15:03.980
I am without those people
significantly influencing me.

01:15:03.980 --> 01:15:06.740
So ask, reach out, a
lot of times people

01:15:06.740 --> 01:15:08.822
are more than happy to help.

01:15:08.822 --> 01:15:11.030
We might think that they're
not and they're too busy,

01:15:11.030 --> 01:15:14.040
or they had this going on,
that's totally not true.

01:15:14.040 --> 01:15:17.365
- I think, with that, I'd like
to open it up to questions.

01:15:17.365 --> 01:15:19.490
And those of you who have
been to other conferences

01:15:19.490 --> 01:15:22.220
know the drill, but maybe
some of you are new to it.

01:15:22.220 --> 01:15:24.710
There's a microphone in
the middle of the aisle.

01:15:24.710 --> 01:15:28.700
We ask you to come up,
to identify yourself,

01:15:28.700 --> 01:15:33.876
and to frame it as a question.

01:15:33.876 --> 01:15:35.750
You're welcome to frame
it to the whole panel

01:15:35.750 --> 01:15:41.390
or to a specific panelist,
not to go into a comment,

01:15:41.390 --> 01:15:46.220
and that way we can get as
many questions in as possible.

01:15:46.220 --> 01:15:48.350
So if you'll start, please.

01:15:48.350 --> 01:15:52.520
- Hi, I'm Elizabeth
Guggenheimer and when

01:15:52.520 --> 01:15:56.340
the 2012 women's
Olympic team came back

01:15:56.340 --> 01:15:59.190
or when they were
competing, I thought

01:15:59.190 --> 01:16:02.160
this is going to bust
that stereotype of women

01:16:02.160 --> 01:16:05.340
not being competitive.

01:16:05.340 --> 01:16:11.700
And then the 2016 Olympics
team, the women right, they

01:16:11.700 --> 01:16:15.600
outshined the men,
and somehow I think

01:16:15.600 --> 01:16:19.710
the question of women being
competitive is kind of still

01:16:19.710 --> 01:16:20.790
out there.

01:16:20.790 --> 01:16:24.990
And the other thing that
goes with this idea that

01:16:24.990 --> 01:16:28.200
being collaborative means
you can't be competitive.

01:16:28.200 --> 01:16:30.840
And the most
dramatic illustration

01:16:30.840 --> 01:16:33.720
of this that I
saw, collaborative

01:16:33.720 --> 01:16:36.750
plus competitive,
was last Sunday,

01:16:36.750 --> 01:16:39.900
the Oxford and
Cambridge boat race

01:16:39.900 --> 01:16:44.640
that the Cambridge women, when
they won and they were just

01:16:44.640 --> 01:16:48.780
joyous, collaborative,
they didn't look exhausted,

01:16:48.780 --> 01:16:52.470
and yet they were full
of the joys of having

01:16:52.470 --> 01:16:53.350
been competitive.

01:16:53.350 --> 01:16:58.500
So I just wonder if we can
get through that stereotype.

01:16:58.500 --> 01:17:02.940
I'd love to hear her thoughts.

01:17:02.940 --> 01:17:04.966
- OK it's a rowing event.

01:17:04.966 --> 01:17:05.466
[CHUCKLES]

01:17:05.466 --> 01:17:06.885
- Yes, it's yours, Anita.

01:17:06.885 --> 01:17:07.620
- Mine.

01:17:07.620 --> 01:17:10.830
And rowing was the very
first intercollegiate sport

01:17:10.830 --> 01:17:14.100
where Yale and Harvard lined
up, lo, those many years ago--

01:17:14.100 --> 01:17:18.530
1852-- to compete and
it's continued since then.

01:17:18.530 --> 01:17:21.540
Collaborative, the
sport of ruling is the--

01:17:21.540 --> 01:17:23.610
I call it the
ultimate team sport.

01:17:23.610 --> 01:17:24.840
you have to collaborate.

01:17:24.840 --> 01:17:28.350
You can't say I'll be back in a
couple of strokes and help out.

01:17:28.350 --> 01:17:28.980
See you then.

01:17:32.250 --> 01:17:34.890
It's a team sport, and yet it's
called an individual sport,

01:17:34.890 --> 01:17:35.520
oddly enough.

01:17:35.520 --> 01:17:37.770
There's so many confusions.

01:17:37.770 --> 01:17:41.339
How can you not be competitive
driving someplace today.

01:17:41.339 --> 01:17:42.630
How can you not be competitive?

01:17:42.630 --> 01:17:45.004
For example, you want
to get that space,

01:17:45.004 --> 01:17:46.420
and there's a car
in front of you,

01:17:46.420 --> 01:17:48.253
and you know they're
going to get the space.

01:17:48.253 --> 01:17:51.690
Life is about competition
in so many ways,

01:17:51.690 --> 01:17:54.360
and for an individual not
to be able to compete,

01:17:54.360 --> 01:17:58.110
is to have to not be
prepared for today's society.

01:18:00.354 --> 01:18:02.520
I mean, there were terrible
things being told to me.

01:18:02.520 --> 01:18:06.060
I had no idea that
when I started college

01:18:06.060 --> 01:18:10.950
that I was going to embark
upon a college sports

01:18:10.950 --> 01:18:13.110
where it was not supposed
to be competitive,

01:18:13.110 --> 01:18:15.960
because after all, we're
supposed to be young ladies,

01:18:15.960 --> 01:18:18.210
and competition
is something bad.

01:18:18.210 --> 01:18:20.160
It just never occurred
to me that that

01:18:20.160 --> 01:18:23.730
would be the type of
collegiate experience

01:18:23.730 --> 01:18:28.290
that was being offered
to women at that time.

01:18:28.290 --> 01:18:31.620
When and where you're
born is so important

01:18:31.620 --> 01:18:36.030
and the time was just right
because things were changing.

01:18:36.030 --> 01:18:39.540
I don't know how many of you
are a part of that era where

01:18:39.540 --> 01:18:40.980
competition was bad.

01:18:40.980 --> 01:18:43.830
You were supposed to learn
skills, that was good,

01:18:43.830 --> 01:18:45.532
but that was enough.

01:18:45.532 --> 01:18:47.490
It's just a terrible
thing to do to tell people

01:18:47.490 --> 01:18:49.830
that you can learn a skill,
but never put it into action

01:18:49.830 --> 01:18:52.350
and test it.

01:18:52.350 --> 01:18:55.410
- I think we live in a-- so the
first part of that question,

01:18:55.410 --> 01:19:00.720
we live in a media culture
and the control of what gets

01:19:00.720 --> 01:19:04.350
on television does not rest
with those who are enthusiastic

01:19:04.350 --> 01:19:08.220
about women's sports, especially
here in the United States.

01:19:08.220 --> 01:19:11.700
And as a result,
it's this dilemma

01:19:11.700 --> 01:19:14.010
that you so aptly expressed.

01:19:14.010 --> 01:19:17.220
Once every four years we see
this bright light of talent

01:19:17.220 --> 01:19:19.740
and then it disappears.

01:19:19.740 --> 01:19:24.450
And society places a value
on the amount of exposure

01:19:24.450 --> 01:19:25.950
and who they see.

01:19:25.950 --> 01:19:28.140
And so when did
women disappear, they

01:19:28.140 --> 01:19:32.790
must not have quality staying
power in terms of athletes.

01:19:32.790 --> 01:19:38.310
It's some terrible
kind of a conclusion.

01:19:38.310 --> 01:19:43.020
And until our
digital environment

01:19:43.020 --> 01:19:48.120
enables us to catch
up on television--

01:19:48.120 --> 01:19:50.760
our media platforms are
such that they're not

01:19:50.760 --> 01:19:54.344
under the control of the people
that they're under control

01:19:54.344 --> 01:19:56.010
right now, I'm not
sure that we're going

01:19:56.010 --> 01:19:57.630
to make a change like that.

01:19:57.630 --> 01:20:01.170
Domestic television right now is
dominated by the big four men's

01:20:01.170 --> 01:20:05.280
sports and each of
our major distributors

01:20:05.280 --> 01:20:07.860
have overpaid for that product.

01:20:07.860 --> 01:20:11.910
And they're so busy now using
every promotional minute,

01:20:11.910 --> 01:20:16.260
every two hours before the
game, two hours after the game,

01:20:16.260 --> 01:20:18.510
every predictable
time and place,

01:20:18.510 --> 01:20:22.770
trying to recapture that money,
that there are no media rights

01:20:22.770 --> 01:20:24.660
fees for women's sports
in the United States.

01:20:28.640 --> 01:20:32.040
Do you see a solution other than
a digital solution [INAUDIBLE]

01:20:32.040 --> 01:20:34.020
television.

01:20:34.020 --> 01:20:39.000
- Right now, the IOC is
working on having a channel,

01:20:39.000 --> 01:20:42.360
and it's stepped all over the
US because without the US,

01:20:42.360 --> 01:20:43.260
it's going to work.

01:20:43.260 --> 01:20:48.570
And the deal was made for NBC
to have the actual channel

01:20:48.570 --> 01:20:52.020
in the United States, which
could limit the US Olympic

01:20:52.020 --> 01:20:55.770
team's ability to raise
funds, but we'll see.

01:20:55.770 --> 01:20:57.390
We don't know if
it's going to work

01:20:57.390 --> 01:20:59.610
because we've been taught--

01:20:59.610 --> 01:21:02.389
to point out-- we've been
taught to just wait a while,

01:21:02.389 --> 01:21:03.930
and then the games
will come, and you

01:21:03.930 --> 01:21:05.850
get force fed for
two weeks, and then

01:21:05.850 --> 01:21:08.840
you have to starve for the
next four years, or two years,

01:21:08.840 --> 01:21:10.860
until the next forced
feeling comes along.

01:21:10.860 --> 01:21:12.960
And that was Dick
Ebersol's approach

01:21:12.960 --> 01:21:15.300
to making the games
more valuable,

01:21:15.300 --> 01:21:19.380
but also we are denied the
stories of these athletes

01:21:19.380 --> 01:21:20.880
around the world.

01:21:20.880 --> 01:21:22.720
Euro sport did the opposite.

01:21:22.720 --> 01:21:25.680
They taught you who the athletes
were so you could follow them,

01:21:25.680 --> 01:21:27.600
and then came the
Olympic games, you

01:21:27.600 --> 01:21:31.630
could understand the path that
they had taken to get there.

01:21:31.630 --> 01:21:33.690
So please look at
the Olympic channel.

01:21:33.690 --> 01:21:34.830
It's digital now.

01:21:34.830 --> 01:21:40.590
I think it comes onto
a channel platform

01:21:40.590 --> 01:21:44.100
and by July, if not sooner, NBC.

01:21:44.100 --> 01:21:46.117
- Let's move on to
another question.

01:21:46.117 --> 01:21:48.450
- Well, actually I was going
to-- my name is Jane Regan.

01:21:48.450 --> 01:21:49.930
I'm a journalist.

01:21:49.930 --> 01:21:52.050
But I don't do
sports journalism,

01:21:52.050 --> 01:21:54.060
that's one reason I came.

01:21:54.060 --> 01:21:56.250
I also teach journalism
and my question

01:21:56.250 --> 01:21:59.820
is exactly related to Donna's
comment and the other comments.

01:21:59.820 --> 01:22:03.630
I'm wondering if in the
women's sports world,

01:22:03.630 --> 01:22:07.050
maybe in the journalism world,
or sports journalism world,

01:22:07.050 --> 01:22:10.410
are there pressure groups,
or associations, or movements

01:22:10.410 --> 01:22:13.650
to put pressures on
the news organizations

01:22:13.650 --> 01:22:17.280
and the newsrooms to include,
and to go out and recruit,

01:22:17.280 --> 01:22:19.710
and include more female
journalists, and sports

01:22:19.710 --> 01:22:20.700
journalists.

01:22:20.700 --> 01:22:23.580
Because certainly,
there are movements

01:22:23.580 --> 01:22:25.770
that have not been
that successful,

01:22:25.770 --> 01:22:30.180
and it goes up and down,
but of journalists of color.

01:22:30.180 --> 01:22:35.100
There is than non-journalists
and editors and stuff of color,

01:22:35.100 --> 01:22:38.850
feel it acutely, the
whiteness of their newsrooms.

01:22:38.850 --> 01:22:43.410
And so there are great
proactive activities

01:22:43.410 --> 01:22:44.970
that the bigger
media outlets do,

01:22:44.970 --> 01:22:48.300
that the bigger universities
do to recruit, and promote,

01:22:48.300 --> 01:22:50.340
and encourage
journalists of color.

01:22:50.340 --> 01:22:54.310
I'm wondering if you know of,
or if we could all take part in

01:22:54.310 --> 01:22:59.190
somehow, something similar
for female sports journalists.

01:22:59.190 --> 01:23:03.030
Because I agree that
our society is so

01:23:03.030 --> 01:23:06.900
influenced what's on the box,
or on the tablet, or whatever,

01:23:06.900 --> 01:23:10.900
and it's all-male sports, except
for once every four years.

01:23:10.900 --> 01:23:15.360
So that's my question
and provocation.

01:23:15.360 --> 01:23:18.320
- There are organization
[INAUDIBLE] Women in Sports

01:23:18.320 --> 01:23:22.350
and Entertainment is one
such group that promotes

01:23:22.350 --> 01:23:25.200
women's sport journalism.

01:23:25.200 --> 01:23:29.012
- Association for Women
in the Sports Media.

01:23:29.012 --> 01:23:32.190
- There are some
groups out there.

01:23:32.190 --> 01:23:36.210
- I despair because now
there's such direct access

01:23:36.210 --> 01:23:39.150
through the digital world.

01:23:39.150 --> 01:23:40.650
I can't do it all,
I wish I could.

01:23:40.650 --> 01:23:43.980
I don't understand
why we're not doing

01:23:43.980 --> 01:23:47.010
more of telling the stories
and telling it directly.

01:23:47.010 --> 01:23:48.390
But we're not,
and I don't why, I

01:23:48.390 --> 01:23:51.130
guess because everybody's busy.

01:23:51.130 --> 01:23:54.580
But it seems logically that once
the world opened up for people

01:23:54.580 --> 01:23:57.366
to be able to directly
communicate, and to have

01:23:57.366 --> 01:23:59.740
networking, and be able to
get the information out there,

01:23:59.740 --> 01:24:00.940
that it would.

01:24:00.940 --> 01:24:04.010
- In terms of putting advocacy
pressure on the system,

01:24:04.010 --> 01:24:05.260
it will also start with data.

01:24:05.260 --> 01:24:08.710
And I have to applaud
AP, Associated Press,

01:24:08.710 --> 01:24:12.601
for at least starting to keep
a report card on sports editors

01:24:12.601 --> 01:24:13.100
and--

01:24:13.100 --> 01:24:16.190
- Guidelines.

01:24:16.190 --> 01:24:19.480
- Who is in our system
and I think we just

01:24:19.480 --> 01:24:22.220
have to do more of that.

01:24:22.220 --> 01:24:27.280
And TIDES, Dick Lapchick's
group in Florida,

01:24:27.280 --> 01:24:29.440
keeps it to an
extent, but I think

01:24:29.440 --> 01:24:33.160
we have to get more data
about the discrepancies,

01:24:33.160 --> 01:24:36.910
and that is going
to ignite advocacy.

01:24:36.910 --> 01:24:40.260
Hopefully that's the path.

01:24:40.260 --> 01:24:43.220
- I think that really is
a challenge to all of us

01:24:43.220 --> 01:24:45.650
to really always be counting.

01:24:45.650 --> 01:24:48.350
Counting how many women,
how many people of color,

01:24:48.350 --> 01:24:52.160
how many people with
disabilities, because if you

01:24:52.160 --> 01:24:53.660
don't, and then
demanding that it

01:24:53.660 --> 01:24:55.190
changed-- because
if you don't, it

01:24:55.190 --> 01:24:58.700
reverts to white male control.

01:24:58.700 --> 01:25:02.060
And I think that what we have
to avoid is a sense of well,

01:25:02.060 --> 01:25:05.970
nobody in this room
is smug or satisfied,

01:25:05.970 --> 01:25:09.260
but if you just sort of accept
it as business as usual,

01:25:09.260 --> 01:25:10.820
the progress is going to stop.

01:25:10.820 --> 01:25:13.490
It may not backslide
all that far back,

01:25:13.490 --> 01:25:15.950
but you have to just
keep staying vigilant.

01:25:15.950 --> 01:25:19.370
And all the things that we're
saying-- here it is, 2017,

01:25:19.370 --> 01:25:21.530
and we're still
raising these issues.

01:25:21.530 --> 01:25:24.080
And I think we just have
to stay on top of it

01:25:24.080 --> 01:25:27.030
because the problem is
there and it's deep.

01:25:27.030 --> 01:25:28.580
- Just one more point on that.

01:25:28.580 --> 01:25:31.752
I think one of the great
things that has happened--

01:25:31.752 --> 01:25:33.710
the only great thing that
has happened in terms

01:25:33.710 --> 01:25:36.750
of Trump's election is--

01:25:36.750 --> 01:25:37.970
no, seriously.

01:25:37.970 --> 01:25:42.860
We have finally had a
catalyst from moving

01:25:42.860 --> 01:25:47.630
from identity politics to
all for one and one for all.

01:25:47.630 --> 01:25:49.550
And you're seeing that
at the grassroots level

01:25:49.550 --> 01:25:53.150
now that if you can
give me the data

01:25:53.150 --> 01:25:56.420
point, if you can
give me a reason,

01:25:56.420 --> 01:25:58.790
everybody is going to help me.

01:25:58.790 --> 01:26:01.600
Now do this.

01:26:01.600 --> 01:26:03.530
That has not existed before.

01:26:03.530 --> 01:26:07.730
We've stayed in a Black
Lives Matter silo.

01:26:07.730 --> 01:26:10.130
We've stayed in a woman's silo.

01:26:10.130 --> 01:26:12.680
And now I'm seeing
something I've never

01:26:12.680 --> 01:26:16.730
seen before in terms of
a lot of people jumping

01:26:16.730 --> 01:26:20.840
into issues that aren't theirs.

01:26:20.840 --> 01:26:21.940
- Another question.

01:26:21.940 --> 01:26:23.740
- Hi, my name is Karen Flynn.

01:26:23.740 --> 01:26:26.640
I'm from the Harvard
summer school.

01:26:26.640 --> 01:26:29.559
I have a question about how--

01:26:29.559 --> 01:26:31.600
or I wanted to see if the
panelists could comment

01:26:31.600 --> 01:26:37.210
on how sports are organized
by gender, just fundamentally,

01:26:37.210 --> 01:26:40.870
and whether you can see
that potentially changing

01:26:40.870 --> 01:26:42.592
in the future.

01:26:42.592 --> 01:26:44.050
In other words,
whether there could

01:26:44.050 --> 01:26:47.500
be an opportunity for girls
to play against girls,

01:26:47.500 --> 01:26:51.610
and women to play against women,
but also to try to break down

01:26:51.610 --> 01:26:55.120
that complete
separation by gender

01:26:55.120 --> 01:26:58.210
that exists in sports
because I think

01:26:58.210 --> 01:27:03.550
that that separation,
in itself, underscores

01:27:03.550 --> 01:27:08.060
a sense of inferiority
about women in sports.

01:27:08.060 --> 01:27:11.680
So can you see potential
in future decades

01:27:11.680 --> 01:27:12.612
for that to change?

01:27:12.612 --> 01:27:14.320
- Stephanie, do you
want to talk to that?

01:27:14.320 --> 01:27:17.200
Because in some ways
I think your model--

01:27:17.200 --> 01:27:19.990
- Sure.

01:27:19.990 --> 01:27:23.590
In a lot of disability sport,
we do that out of necessity

01:27:23.590 --> 01:27:26.080
initially because just
with the critical mass.

01:27:26.080 --> 01:27:29.710
And so I can speak from
a wheelchair basketball

01:27:29.710 --> 01:27:32.500
perspective, where we
have teams that are coed,

01:27:32.500 --> 01:27:36.370
or teams that compete either--

01:27:36.370 --> 01:27:38.350
I've played on
full women's teams

01:27:38.350 --> 01:27:40.060
that compete against
full men's teams.

01:27:44.570 --> 01:27:48.260
One of the ways that our
organization incorrectly,

01:27:48.260 --> 01:27:50.540
I think, tries to--

01:27:50.540 --> 01:27:53.150
they call it, "accommodate"
for that, and without getting

01:27:53.150 --> 01:27:56.270
into a sort of a long
discussion about our sport,

01:27:56.270 --> 01:27:58.460
with wheelchair basketball
you have a wide range

01:27:58.460 --> 01:27:59.780
of disabilities that can play.

01:27:59.780 --> 01:28:01.571
And so in order to
level the playing field,

01:28:01.571 --> 01:28:05.240
you have this classification
system based on that,

01:28:05.240 --> 01:28:07.530
and you're seeing a point value.

01:28:07.530 --> 01:28:10.340
And one of the ways,
globally and in the US that--

01:28:10.340 --> 01:28:13.340
and I think it actually does
a complete disservice to women

01:28:13.340 --> 01:28:18.320
athletes within our sport,
is if you're rated as a 2.5,

01:28:18.320 --> 01:28:20.720
then if you play on a men's
team, you go one point down.

01:28:24.110 --> 01:28:27.140
It's absurd, absolutely absurd.

01:28:27.140 --> 01:28:29.870
So I think we're kind
of already doing it.

01:28:29.870 --> 01:28:31.880
We don't do it in
the most perfect way,

01:28:31.880 --> 01:28:35.060
I don't think, because if we do
have women included on teams,

01:28:35.060 --> 01:28:41.480
they're treated as of lower
value, and in essence,

01:28:41.480 --> 01:28:43.550
sometimes become like
pylons on the court.

01:28:43.550 --> 01:28:45.650
They're just there to be there.

01:28:45.650 --> 01:28:47.900
So while we do this
out of necessity,

01:28:47.900 --> 01:28:49.760
I don't think we do it
very well right now.

01:28:49.760 --> 01:28:52.730
I think in order for
disability sport to grow,

01:28:52.730 --> 01:28:56.630
I think there's going to have to
be coeducational opportunities

01:28:56.630 --> 01:28:58.910
just because there
isn't the critical mass.

01:28:58.910 --> 01:29:02.329
And while it might
address what you

01:29:02.329 --> 01:29:04.370
were talking about with
the inferiority of women,

01:29:04.370 --> 01:29:06.161
I think it has to be
done in the right way.

01:29:06.161 --> 01:29:08.870
And I think that
classification example for us

01:29:08.870 --> 01:29:12.260
is a way that it's not
being done in the right way.

01:29:12.260 --> 01:29:15.500
I would much rather see them
play at whatever classification

01:29:15.500 --> 01:29:17.360
they are, they hold
value, they bring

01:29:17.360 --> 01:29:20.960
what they bring to the team,
and then it's a non issue then

01:29:20.960 --> 01:29:21.920
at that point.

01:29:21.920 --> 01:29:24.440
So we're sort of
there right now.

01:29:27.190 --> 01:29:32.720
- We had that very interesting
discussion when we're

01:29:32.720 --> 01:29:35.810
redrafting the Olympic Charter.

01:29:35.810 --> 01:29:38.060
And I was the only woman in
the room among attorneys,

01:29:38.060 --> 01:29:40.550
and we're talking
about equality,

01:29:40.550 --> 01:29:43.210
and so the other guy, well,
you know, women and men,

01:29:43.210 --> 01:29:44.600
they're not equal.

01:29:44.600 --> 01:29:46.250
And I said, what do you mean?

01:29:46.250 --> 01:29:48.200
And they said,
well, you know, they

01:29:48.200 --> 01:29:51.530
have the heavyweight
boxing gold medal,

01:29:51.530 --> 01:29:55.414
and then they have the feather
weight boxing gold medal,

01:29:55.414 --> 01:29:57.080
and you would never
put a feather weight

01:29:57.080 --> 01:29:58.410
against a heavyweight.

01:29:58.410 --> 01:29:59.960
I said, no, of course not.

01:29:59.960 --> 01:30:03.620
And so that's not equal, I
said, but are the medals gold?

01:30:03.620 --> 01:30:05.770
Are they the same medals?

01:30:05.770 --> 01:30:06.962
The same champions?

01:30:06.962 --> 01:30:08.420
And he said, well,
yeah [INAUDIBLE]

01:30:08.420 --> 01:30:13.220
Listen guys, men and
women are different,

01:30:13.220 --> 01:30:15.170
and thank goodness
for the difference,

01:30:15.170 --> 01:30:17.090
but can anyone in
this room tell me

01:30:17.090 --> 01:30:20.990
that we are not absolutely
unequivocally and forever

01:30:20.990 --> 01:30:22.837
equally human?

01:30:22.837 --> 01:30:24.170
That's what we're talking about.

01:30:24.170 --> 01:30:26.990
We are equally
human and therefore

01:30:26.990 --> 01:30:30.080
once you go from there, you
stay on a level playing field

01:30:30.080 --> 01:30:33.530
with respect and treating
people with respect.

01:30:33.530 --> 01:30:36.110
And that's how we got sex
back into the Olympic Charter.

01:30:39.840 --> 01:30:43.910
- We do a great job in
intramural in doing this

01:30:43.910 --> 01:30:47.450
because we specify how
many men and how many

01:30:47.450 --> 01:30:49.430
women are on the same
team, and in many cases,

01:30:49.430 --> 01:30:52.070
don't make any other
rules adjustments at all.

01:30:52.070 --> 01:30:55.130
In some cases we do,
but we have to change

01:30:55.130 --> 01:30:57.860
the rules of these
sports that have

01:30:57.860 --> 01:31:01.040
become cultural
rituals, which is what

01:31:01.040 --> 01:31:02.780
makes it so difficult to do.

01:31:02.780 --> 01:31:06.610
We know how to do it, but
the willingness isn't there.

01:31:09.280 --> 01:31:11.630
- Hi, I'm Lily Judan, a
senior at the college,

01:31:11.630 --> 01:31:14.870
and I had a question about
the role of female athletes

01:31:14.870 --> 01:31:16.220
as advocates.

01:31:16.220 --> 01:31:20.450
And my question is, is it fair
to ask all female athletes

01:31:20.450 --> 01:31:23.550
to advocate for their sex?

01:31:23.550 --> 01:31:25.720
Or is there also a role
for female athletes

01:31:25.720 --> 01:31:28.610
just to be athletes
and play without having

01:31:28.610 --> 01:31:31.662
to worry about what their
sex brings to the table?

01:31:31.662 --> 01:31:32.745
- That's a great question.

01:31:36.730 --> 01:31:38.650
- Take athlete out of it.

01:31:38.650 --> 01:31:40.349
Do-- what's her name?

01:31:40.349 --> 01:31:41.140
- I can't remember.

01:31:41.140 --> 01:31:43.200
- She's walking away.

01:31:43.200 --> 01:31:44.870
- She's out of here.

01:31:44.870 --> 01:31:50.770
- So the point is, in the face
of looking at wrong, if you

01:31:50.770 --> 01:31:53.904
stay silent, are you complicit?

01:31:53.904 --> 01:31:54.820
- Exactly.

01:31:54.820 --> 01:31:59.395
- So if you see wrong, do
you have a responsibility

01:31:59.395 --> 01:32:03.100
to advocate, at least
to say it's wrong?

01:32:08.890 --> 01:32:10.280
- My question's relevant.

01:32:10.280 --> 01:32:12.250
I'm Sara [INAUDIBLE]
I'm a staff member here,

01:32:12.250 --> 01:32:15.490
also a graduate of the college
and the softball program,

01:32:15.490 --> 01:32:18.250
and I'm actually curious about
in your different context,

01:32:18.250 --> 01:32:20.980
the role of male athletes
in this equation.

01:32:20.980 --> 01:32:23.800
And I think the US men's
hockey team made a statement

01:32:23.800 --> 01:32:24.940
about the women's plight.

01:32:24.940 --> 01:32:27.760
I couldn't help but wonder,
what if Federer had refused

01:32:27.760 --> 01:32:30.224
to take more money than Serena?

01:32:30.224 --> 01:32:32.890
So I'm curious what you think in
terms of outlook in the future,

01:32:32.890 --> 01:32:35.305
where do male athletes
fit into that equation?

01:32:38.290 --> 01:32:40.090
- I have great hope.

01:32:40.090 --> 01:32:44.950
I really do because we're
seeing the first generation

01:32:44.950 --> 01:32:48.490
of male athletes who are willing
to buck their coaches power

01:32:48.490 --> 01:32:51.805
and the power of the institution
at great personal risk.

01:32:54.430 --> 01:32:56.800
We haven't seen that before.

01:32:56.800 --> 01:32:59.320
We're looking at the
beginnings of unionization

01:32:59.320 --> 01:33:01.540
among college athletes.

01:33:01.540 --> 01:33:04.556
We are now talking about the
right of athletes to speak.

01:33:04.556 --> 01:33:06.430
We're now talking about
the right of athletes

01:33:06.430 --> 01:33:08.410
not to be controlled
by coaches, in terms

01:33:08.410 --> 01:33:11.830
of what they put on Facebook, or
what they put in their Twitter

01:33:11.830 --> 01:33:12.730
account.

01:33:12.730 --> 01:33:16.120
That's a new conversation,
a really new conversation.

01:33:16.120 --> 01:33:19.670
So I'm very hopeful
in that regard.

01:33:19.670 --> 01:33:21.880
- Well, I think in
disability sport

01:33:21.880 --> 01:33:24.380
you kind of have an
interesting intersection

01:33:24.380 --> 01:33:25.640
with disability and gender.

01:33:25.640 --> 01:33:28.976
And so quite often when
you look at male athletes

01:33:28.976 --> 01:33:30.350
with disabilities,
a lot of times

01:33:30.350 --> 01:33:32.930
their fight is coming
from the disability angle

01:33:32.930 --> 01:33:35.300
and they don't bring
gender in with it.

01:33:35.300 --> 01:33:39.410
And so I know we struggle
a little bit with that,

01:33:39.410 --> 01:33:42.020
just to make sure that that
intersection is understood.

01:33:42.020 --> 01:33:43.660
And that kind of
like Donna mentioned,

01:33:43.660 --> 01:33:47.150
we can't stay in our
silo in those moments.

01:33:47.150 --> 01:33:51.470
And so if you're
fighting for your right

01:33:51.470 --> 01:33:54.140
to be able to go compete
as a disabled athlete,

01:33:54.140 --> 01:33:56.020
then it has to be all
disabled athletes.

01:33:56.020 --> 01:33:59.640
It can't just be fighting
for the men or vice versa.

01:33:59.640 --> 01:34:02.660
So I think for us, it's
kind of getting over

01:34:02.660 --> 01:34:05.420
that step of just fighting
it or just advocating

01:34:05.420 --> 01:34:06.890
in your one silo.

01:34:06.890 --> 01:34:10.780
It has to be an across
the board fight.

01:34:10.780 --> 01:34:13.174
- Yeah, there's a
group called RISE,

01:34:13.174 --> 01:34:14.840
and I don't know what
it all stands for,

01:34:14.840 --> 01:34:16.310
but they're working
with athletes

01:34:16.310 --> 01:34:20.060
to help them decide to make the
decision of whether to speak

01:34:20.060 --> 01:34:22.640
up, and what risks that
they face with speaking

01:34:22.640 --> 01:34:26.150
up, and helping them understand
that the risk of not speaking

01:34:26.150 --> 01:34:30.330
up is you go for decades
and years wishing you had,

01:34:30.330 --> 01:34:32.840
and figuring out how to
balance those things.

01:34:32.840 --> 01:34:37.010
Because when you speak up, and
you might find that suddenly

01:34:37.010 --> 01:34:39.740
you're not being given
the same amount of time

01:34:39.740 --> 01:34:41.750
on the field of
play, and you have--

01:34:41.750 --> 01:34:44.960
the coach-athlete dynamic
is a powerful one,

01:34:44.960 --> 01:34:49.175
which needs a lot more
exploration as well.

01:34:49.175 --> 01:34:50.540
Enough said.

01:34:50.540 --> 01:34:52.720
- I say this to young
people all the time.

01:34:52.720 --> 01:34:56.360
That if you feel because of
your personality or your lack

01:34:56.360 --> 01:34:59.210
of even experience
in speaking out,

01:34:59.210 --> 01:35:01.880
that it's not something that's
going to sit well with you,

01:35:01.880 --> 01:35:04.010
find somebody who can.

01:35:04.010 --> 01:35:06.680
Is there a tenured
female faculty member

01:35:06.680 --> 01:35:08.600
who can make your case?

01:35:08.600 --> 01:35:11.880
Is there somebody else on your
team that you can work with?

01:35:11.880 --> 01:35:13.250
You could be the researcher.

01:35:13.250 --> 01:35:14.625
You could be the
one that gathers

01:35:14.625 --> 01:35:17.300
the ammunition and starts
planning what should be said.

01:35:17.300 --> 01:35:19.850
You don't have to actually
absolutely say it,

01:35:19.850 --> 01:35:22.130
you just have to make
sure it gets said.

01:35:25.490 --> 01:35:28.370
- I think we're pretty
much out of time.

01:35:28.370 --> 01:35:31.010
And what I would
like us all to do

01:35:31.010 --> 01:35:32.930
is to thank our
panelists for getting--

